WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
It's rolling.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Today is Sunday, March 17, 2013, Saint Patrick's Day.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
My name is John Dittmer and I'm here in Arlington, Virginia with videographer John Bishop

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
to interview Ms. Don Trump, our Mohawk Holland, a leading activist in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:39.000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:44.000
We're delighted to be here today and we thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Okay. I'd like to begin by asking about your home and family. Where were you born and raised?

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Well, I was born in Washington, D.C. and raised in Arlington, Virginia, basically about a mile down the road.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:09.000
And Buckingham apartments, which at that point were known as being the only place in northern Virginia that would rent to Jews.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And this was early 40s, the folks who come from New York looking for that good government job and the depression

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:27.000
met now starting families and wanted out of the boarding houses and they could move to Buckingham and that was about it.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.000
What did your folks do? What did your dad do?

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.000
Oh, they had those good government jobs.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:45.000
My father came from Southwest Iowa during the Depression and my folks met at the Midnight Shift at the old post office building in the elevator.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:02:03.000
I was a real mad. Mr. Trump. And he, when I was born, was working for the Department of Labor and continued in that, I guess, into well through the 50s and then switched to the Department of State but doing pretty much the same thing.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:11.000
And my mother had worked as a secretary and then became a stay-at-home mom, this was the custom.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
She came from rural Georgia.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:22.000
And what was it like drawing up in Arlington in the 1940s?

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Well, Arlington was definitely the South, maybe not the deep South but everything by law and custom was segregated.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:47.000
So I lived in an all-white world but with so many of my neighbors and their kids with this liberal New York Jewish outlook, I think that was one of the influences on me.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
What about church? Church of California?

00:02:50.000 --> 00:03:04.000
I was a big part of my life as Presbyterian because where my dad grew up, it was a Swedish town and the Lutheran Church which would have been the natural was in Swedish.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:13.000
So all those others were Presbyterians. So I went to the Presbyterian Church that was nearby.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And we memorized all these Bible verses and got our gold star if we could recite it.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And as much as you've done it unto one of the least of these, my brethren, you've done it unto me, do unto others as you would have them do unto you for such as the Kingdom of God, all that stuff.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Saying those songs about Jesus loves the little children, red and yellow, black and white.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:50.000
But the church was segregated by law and of course as soon as we left the church we were continued to be hypocrites.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And that bothered me out sort of a literalist, a better or worse.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So when you were a teenager where you were still going to church? All through my teenage years.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:12.000
What was race ever brought up in any context in Sunday school or from the Paul books?

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:22.000
Not that I remember so openly but I was always going to the Sunday evening youth fellowship.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Once Sunday we were told that next Sunday there would be some colored students coming to meet with us but we were to keep this absolutely quiet.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
We were not to tell our parents, our friends, anybody.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And the reasons being that the American Nazi Party was around the corner for their headquarters and of course it was illegal so the police could come.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And some of the church, I don't know if elders is the word in the Presbyterians but church leaders might be against this and lock us out and fire the minister forth with.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So we kept it quiet and I guess at least twice this same group of students organized through the black why came and had our standards spaghetti dinner with us.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:30.000
And I don't remember what we talked about particularly but this was in the throes of the county wanting to go along with Brown versus board and the state of Virginia and the throes of massive resistance.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
This would have been the late 50s.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:43.000
So I think a lot of it was so that a few students would know each other across racial lines when it became.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And I stayed in touch with one of the girls for a while.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Were these the first real conversation you had with black people?

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Yes and the first with white too.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Years later I tried to track this down a bit and then I should get back to that.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:17.000
There was a county gathering at the school that was the first integrated and I raised the question that anybody could anybody fill me in on how this was organized.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Did the white ministers reach out to the black community reach out to the white ministers.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Was this happening all over the county and we just didn't know about it. Nobody knew a thing.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:35.000
One woman said she thought if anyone knew it would be her mother who was ill and could not make it that night and she would ask her.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
But a week later her mother was dead.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
I'd still like to know.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:48.000
I've heard that it may have been happening a couple other white churches but.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:55.000
In 1955 Emmett Till was murdered. He was your age.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:07.000
For black activists in this house this was a tearing point something that they would never forget and they didn't realize how vulnerable they were and how rotten the system was.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
They didn't already know.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Did the lynching of Till have any impact up here? Were you aware of it?

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
I don't even think I was aware of it. I may have heard of it but it was not a big deal.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.000
That was the same thing in Indiana. I vaguely remember and say, oh that's too bad.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:33.000
But I was grew up down at grandma's in Georgia. There would be discussions of the Leo Frank lynching.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So the eye concept of lynching was not shocking because there would always be these big debates as to whether Leo Frank was innocent or guilty.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And the lynch mob had gone by my aunt's house as I understood it. So lynching was not breaking news.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.000
What was it like at grandma's when you were visiting?

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Oh it was wonderful. Fresh biscuits, every meal and grits and snap beans and great time.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Did you go every year?

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.000
Every year we would go down for two weeks. My mother would load the girls in the car, me and my sister and drive down.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Three day trip back before the interstate.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
Where did your grandma live in Georgia?

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.000
O'Coney, which at that point was a company town out in the swamps for the logging.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
Wow, yeah, I know that area.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:35.000
The town was O'Coney down near Gort-Gartner. It's not O'Coney County.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:50.000
What was it that motivated you to become involved in the civil rights struggle that was just now beginning in the late 1950s with beginning to attract attention?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:59.000
You had Martin Luther King and the Montgomery bus boycott. You had the Little Rock Nine.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Well, I think going back with this memorizing the Bible verses and then we had the Declaration of Independence in high school, we had to memorize it.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And once when I was down at grandma's, I must have been about ten. This girl that I used to hang out with, so they're there at each other to go walk through Niggertown.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:33.000
We called it and just the striking disparity. Of course everyone just sort of evaporated as we saw these two white girls coming down the road.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:44.000
But I could see with my own eyes the difference between the black school and the white school that was the new brick building and all that.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
That really struck me.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And then in high school, the girl next to me in Spanish class had been in one of those jurisdictions in Virginia where the schools were closed.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:08.000
So instead of enjoying her senior year, she was sent to live with relatives or somebody and do an 11th grade a year late.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And just seeing the effect of segregation and knowing the hypocrisy of it from what are founding documents and the Bible, I just sort of felt as a southerner that we needed to change.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And when I have my chance to help do something, I would see it.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Now if you're anticipating my next question, and that is a broader question, that southerners were the first white people to seek out the young black activists in SNCC and CORE, telling them up to people like you, Bob Zellner, Casey Hayden.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:58.000
Why do you think it was southerner, white southerners, who were first in the movement rather than nor theirs?

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Because those Yankees up there were looking down their nose at us.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:18.000
And we were at home. We were working at home on what we saw as our own problems.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:24.000
I think globally, locally, loom where you're planted, those things came in later.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:32.000
But back then, we were very local oriented. Particularly in the south, we had to be able to place people.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:44.000
No, where you were from, who you were related to, very community-minded. A trip to the next state was a big deal for some people to the next county.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And so I think it was natural to be in our community orientation and our deep religious convictions.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:03.000
Okay, she was saying that it was through the Methodist Church going to interracial meetings out of state that she first became involved in activities.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And for me, the Presbyterians, my Presbyterian youth group, and then I went to Duke University because my mother wanted me to go to a name school that was safely segregated.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
What would have been your first choice?

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:40.000
It was some small church school in the north, I think maybe Ohio, but I do understand such a massive high school that it was totally overcrowded with growing suburbia in the 50s that I wanted a small place where you were known for better or worse, but not where you were lost in the mob.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And mother was afraid of integration, the product of her environment, and she was all about status.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So I went to Duke, but it was there after the sit-ins got going in Durham that our Presbyterian chaplain, and I was going to this Sunday evening meetings, told us in this like deja vu that some students from North Carolina College,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:13.000
who were doing the sit-ins, would be coming over.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:26.000
Next week, don't spread the word unless it's somebody you think would really want to come because the administration could lock us out, the police could show up, or the local rowdies could visit us.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:38.000
And these well-spoken students came over and explained all about the sit-ins legally and morally, and at the end invited us to join them.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:39.000
That was my moment.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:49.000
Yes. Before we get to that, what were your impressions? Tell us what Duke was like in 1959.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:59.000
All about status. It was big. It was, well, I don't know, it was literally dripping ivy, but it certainly fits that impression.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:07.000
By chance, the luck of the draw, I had a roommate from New York, not the city, but out that way.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:13.000
And we decided we didn't want to rush with the civil war against the first.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
That was a big decision.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:28.000
The first or second week, you know, you know, you were no more on campus and didn't have your bearings and they had to rush, which meant you got dressed up and went and sat and got picked over by these girls that you didn't know to see if you were suitable for an organization that you were doing.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:33.000
The organization that you really didn't know either, and it cost money.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And the International Club, which was basically graduate school guys, was having a potlup party the same night.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
And we thought, oh, graduate guys, this sounds much better.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
So we went to that.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:55.000
On my lands, too, Duke rather got upset with this. They sent counselors around to see if we were unhappy.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
Was it a financial situation?

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Just because we didn't rush.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:09.000
I heard that it had never happened in the history of the universities before, which I think probably made me all the more determined not to do it.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:13.000
But, you know, graduate school guys were good news.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
So there was a lot of status.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Oh, it was all about status. I'm just what mom wanted.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Yeah. The sit-ins, they started, you were still a freshman.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:27.000
I was a freshman.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
Second semester.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
Yes.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
Tell us about your involvement beginning with that.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:39.000
Well, they invited us to join and a few graduate guys.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
And Lucia and I, fortunately, were roommates.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Went down and got on the picket lines.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And when it came time for a sit-in, which wasn't too long into it, we joined them at the lunch counter.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
I don't have strong memories of it now.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:02.000
You know, the details, but twice in jail.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
It was...

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Were you nervous?

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.000
I mean, this is a big change for the way you were brought up.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:16.000
I don't remember being nervous as such, but in jail, I mean, it was fairly quick.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.000
So the one time to be, and you were surrounded by fellow sit-in folks.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.000
Where were you when you were arrested?

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:27.000
I think it was Cress, but I really couldn't swear to it.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:28.000
Warworth.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And you went in and sat down.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Went in and sat down.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
You had an integrated group.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:38.000
And I don't remember if the white sat down first or not, but there weren't that many whites.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.000
So I suspect we just sort of went in and sat down.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Were you told to leave or were we just arrested right away?

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
I don't remember, but generally you were asked to leave.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:56.000
But in jail, the whites were...

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:02.000
That's where it could have its potential for being scary that you were in with the regular white prisoners or by yourself.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And you didn't know what would happen.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
But I think some of the guys were roughed up.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
Well, one of my favorite moments comes out of that.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:16.000
When after we got out of jail and we were talking about it with the black students,

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:21.000
then had a pretty good time because Durham was not the deep south.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
They had made the most of it.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And they once they realized that the white students didn't have quite such a good time,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
they came up with a plan.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And all of us had Native American ancestry or claim to black and white.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
So North Carolina state law.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:48.000
Someone checked it, provided for separate cells, for white men, white women, colored men, colored women, and others.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:53.000
Didn't say anything about men, others, and women, others, just others.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And so we decided we would all be others.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
We had arrested on Friday.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
We refused bail.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:07.000
And system being locked up together in one cell and party all weekend.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:11.000
And make bail Monday morning to get the class.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
Did it work?

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
No, attorney McKissick said that was frivolous.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
But it was a great plan.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.000
The other moment from that, I understand we would have been expelled.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:28.000
The administration at Duke wanted to kick us out and call this over to the Dean's office.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:33.000
When we got back from jail, there was a note in our mailbox saying to call the Dean.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:37.000
And she wanted us to report to her office, which was my now it's after dark.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:42.000
And it's the only light on in the building.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:45.000
I had to walk over to this administrative building.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And we came in and she locked the door and put the key in her pocket.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:58.000
And we had quite a little discussion and had we called our parents.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
Well, of course, neither one of us had.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
LeCia and me.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
So there's the phone.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:12.000
And obviously we weren't getting out and she had the key in her pocket until we made the phone call.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:20.000
And I've understood since then that we would have been expelled except the professional organization for the professors.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And they were associated.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
Yeah, they intervened.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:32.000
But I remember telling one of my English teachers, my English teacher that going on,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.000
Sidden was coming up and if I were in jail and he gave a pop quiz, could I make it up?

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
Because he was good at pop quizzes.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:45.000
And he sort of laughed and smiled and said, no, I'll just bring it down to the jail.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:48.000
You can't cheat in there.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
I asked him to wonder.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And so we had support from the faculty, just not from the administration.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Did Duke have a separate women's and men's college men?

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:01.000
Yeah.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And you were in the role of campus.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Yeah.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:08.000
And so it was that you were very much isolated there.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:13.000
I said, now there was a bus that ran between campuses and you might,

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:20.000
particularly after your freshman year, crossed over to the other campus for a class or especially event in the chapel.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:25.000
And because the men's campus had the chapel.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:29.000
What was that phone call like to your mother?

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:30.000
Couldn't have been good.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.000
I don't remember a whole lot about it.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:36.000
You've spoken very openly about your mother being a segregationist.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:40.000
Yeah, product of her environment.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:44.000
My mother, I've heard in recent years from one of her friends,

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:49.000
thought I had been sort of sucked up into a cult.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:52.000
So you need to be debriefed or deprogrammed?

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
A brainwashed out of it.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And plus it went against everything she had grown up and believed in.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
I can say that a little more generously now than I could have then.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:08.000
So was there tension at home when you went home?

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:11.000
Oh yeah, lots of tensions.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:17.000
And I don't think things really got on anything like a normal footing.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:22.000
Never really normal, but I like it until the grandkids came along.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
How did your dad react to all this?

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:32.000
Well, my dad, I think first and foremost, was afraid his darling daughter was going to get killed.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:38.000
And being a good government bureaucrat, he believed in working from the top down.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:42.000
Brown versus board versus take it to the streets.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.000
With the demonstration, you might have an effect very locally,

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:52.000
but there was all the rest of the area that took a Supreme Court decision.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
And, John, let's follow the...

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:57.000
Okay, we'll go back.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
Well, so you had your freshman year at Duke.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
Did you go back? Where were you in the fall?

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:02.000
I dropped out.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:08.000
And the fall, I was out of school working on the hill.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.000
Talk about that.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:19.000
By fall, I was living in DC.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.000
On your own.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.000
On my own.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And I think my...

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.000
Well, trying to remember exactly.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:34.000
I'd gotten back the government job I'd had,

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:43.000
which was a summer temp that I'd had making money to go to college down at the FCC.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:50.000
And that ran out, and then I ended up getting a job with some Wisconsin senator.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:56.000
Just very menial office work and then Senator Engel eventually.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:02.000
But I had joined up with the Howard Group, nonviolent action group.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:07.000
Now, that is something that I want you to talk about a little bit more.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:14.000
This was, for that time, probably the most militant group of activists that were around.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:19.000
How did you just walk onto the Howard campus?

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:20.000
Yeah, well...

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.000
When I left, was leaving North Carolina,

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:27.000
some of the students at NCC said, well, now we haven't heard anything from Howard

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:31.000
since the founding meeting of SNCC.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
It's sure that it used to break.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
And we haven't heard anything from them.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.000
So when you get up there, go up to Howard and find out what's happening.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:42.000
And if they're not doing anything, get something going.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:47.000
Well, of course, I had no clue where Howard really was going up in Arlington.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:55.000
But I got there and was walking around campus, looking lost and asking people,

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:00.000
stopping them, you know, knowing anybody who was involved with student demonstrations

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:03.000
or sit-ins and what have you.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:06.000
I understand that there had been having sympathy pickets,

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:11.000
it's a downtown war worth and things like that.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:16.000
But there was a meeting plan that night or the next or something to talk about sit-ins.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:20.000
They were planning, is it turned out, to go to Arlington?

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:24.000
Because I think some diplomatic sorts have been denied service.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.000
Well, I was from Arlington.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:32.000
I had a little experience with sit-ins and jails, so I was welcomed into the group.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
Now, it wasn't just students at Howard University.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:43.000
It was people from the community, some with core affiliations and what have you and possibly,

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:47.000
I think, other universities in town.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:54.000
And so we went out to Arlington and sat in and the American Nazi Party showed up

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.000
and went to the local high school and encouraged kids getting out of school

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:02.000
to come up where we were sitting down in Cherrydale.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.000
Who were the activists that you remember from that?

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Well, the main leaders were two older guys, you know, in their mid-20s, maybe.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:23.000
NAG cohort and NAG cohort, who was, Paul was white.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:28.000
Lawrence was a Divinity School student and there was NAG cohort,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:35.000
who's went on to be a doctor and there was NAG cohort, who's still around.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.000
We gave a full-time activist.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:40.000
Oh, yeah.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:44.000
Those are the main ones I remember.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
Was Stokeley there then?

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:54.000
No, Stokeley apparently came down with a group from New York to see what was happening

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:00.000
with the students in D.C., but he was not a Howard student until that fall.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
So you were really there before?

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.000
Stokeley came and Cleave Sellers and others who?

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:10.000
Yeah, this was not a particularly militant group then.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:11.000
It was integrated.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.000
It was integrated.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:18.000
When and Connie Greene, I have a whole list of them upstairs.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:23.000
Somebody who's writing a book just asked who was it, those counters that I got out the old clippings

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:28.000
and wrote down all the names about a month ago.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:32.000
I think there were about 13 of us to be 12 or 13 the first day.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:38.000
We sat at one place, I think the drug fair, which is now gone,

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
and then we some moved down to people.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:46.000
I mean, they closed the counters, but did not ask the police to arrest us or anything,

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:51.000
but crowds were coming in because school was letting out.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:56.000
I really think that I haven't researched this or know that these were local chains,

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:08.000
locally owned, peoples and drug fair, probably with the same sort of liberal New York Jewish connections,

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:13.000
the founders of the owners, and particularly drug fair I know was,

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:20.000
and that they were not going to break the state law by integrating.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.000
They were sort of waiting to be forced.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:28.000
And after about a week of demonstrations, including down at Woolworths and Sheryl England,

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:32.000
right near where we ate,

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:40.000
now we had a couple of department stores also, so locally owned chains, New York Jewish.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:45.000
We had a cooling off period, negotiating period, the last of about a week,

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.000
and then lo and behold, they were open.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:53.000
So in retrospect, I really think they were just waiting to have their hand forced,

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:57.000
and they said, they serve everybody and the police said,

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:01.000
well, they weren't going to take the initiative to enforce segregation laws,

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
if they wanted to serve us.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:04.000
No, water was water.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
What was shown to you on the picture?

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:09.000
That's just run a little bit around here.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
That's pretty much that's pretty.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
You can be comfortable, this is starting to run well.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:14.000
Oh, sorry.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:19.000
I see you.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.000
Now I lost one trick at the moment.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:23.000
I'm going to stop.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:24.000
Yeah, I'm ready.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:25.000
We're going.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.000
Did you or an Arlington, did anybody recognize you?

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.000
I don't think so.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
Well, folks, it didn't make the newspapers.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:33.000
Well, it made the-

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.000
Why did your old was stirring up trouble?

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:43.000
It made pictures in the newspaper, but I don't think anybody really connected this with them.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:46.000
My family had moved out to Fairfax County by then,

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:51.000
and if anyone connected this, I didn't hear about it.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.000
And what next happened with NAG?

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:00.000
Talk about your, that old period of your life?

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:04.000
Well, the lunch counters were integrated.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:05.000
School year was over.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
What are we going to do now?

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.000
Let's take it to the beach.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:13.000
But of course, the beaches were a bit of a drive.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.000
Couldn't really commute back and forth on that one so easily.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
So, Glen Echo Amusement Park became the next one.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:24.000
And I wasn't in on the planning end of things.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.000
I just show up after work.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:27.000
What was Glen Echo Amusement Park?

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:30.000
Glen Echo Amusement Park was in a-

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:31.000
Disney of its day.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:38.000
It was an amusement park, and it was where quite Washington went for summer fun.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:41.000
And of course, segregated.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:44.000
And the-

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:49.000
There was a Bannockburn, MD community,

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:57.000
which was sort of a co-op community of the same sort of Jews who had lived in Buckingham,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:01.000
and then after World War II, were buying wanting housing.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:04.000
And of course, there were restrictive covenants and a lot of the housing.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:08.000
So, they started this community over in New York,

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
in New York, in Maryland.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:15.000
And they had been pushing the county-

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:17.000
Montgomery County-

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:21.000
was sending in the summer programs the white kids to swim at Glen Echo Amusement Park,

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:25.000
and the black kids into DC.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.000
And they wanted-

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
everyone to go to the same place.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.000
Glen Echo Amusement Park.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:31.000
So, they were-

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
had been petitioning the county,

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:36.000
you know, starting to raise a ruckus on this.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:42.000
And I don't know how much some of the folks in Nag may have been aware of this,

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:46.000
but anyway, we all ended up at the same place.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:52.000
And I and maybe some other folks could, of course, buy tickets.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.000
You had individual-

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.000
you had tickets, and if you wanted a ride,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
you gave a ticket for the ride.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
And I went and bought a whole bunch of tickets,

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:04.000
and handed them over to the black students,

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:08.000
who then could go zooming through the arch

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:11.000
and down to the merry-go-round or whatever,

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:15.000
and get arrested on the merry-go-round,

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:20.000
which, of course, doesn't have a back to be at.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:24.000
And this later got into the whole issue

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:31.000
as I understand it, of private security guards

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:37.000
or whatever being used to enforce the state law or whatever.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.000
But they used the private guards

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
and making an arrest on this.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:46.000
And so, after they were arrested,

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:49.000
it became a summer-long picket,

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
with strong support from the Banickburn community,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:55.000
of union-made signs and sandwiches,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
and picking us up the non-hot days,

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
and taking over to their homes,

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:02.000
for a little R&R and lemonade and pit stops.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:06.000
And the American Nazi party was out again.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.000
Was that American Nazi Party?

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:08.000
Yes, American Nazi Party,

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.000
he made it to the lunch counters in Arlington,

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:14.000
with Swatztikos and he made it to Gleneco,

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:18.000
which got a little tense because you had folks

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.000
from the World War II concentration camps

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
with numbers on their arms.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:29.000
So the police required a certain degrees of separation.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:31.000
So you had tickets and counter-pickets,

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.000
and occasionally somebody driving by the road there

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
and yelling something or throwing a little something.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:41.000
But basically, it was just pretty long-peaceful.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:44.000
Yes, that's what happened.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:49.000
Close-segregated and the next year it opened integrative.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.000
So another victory.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:56.000
Another victory, but the days of places like Gleneco

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:04.000
were numbered, small, non-chain amusement parks.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:07.000
Plus, they stopped running the trolley out there,

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:10.000
which was the main way folks got out there.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:13.000
The trolley ride out as a kid was almost as exciting

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
as being in the amusement park.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:17.000
So you had frequented the park?

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:18.000
Oh, yeah.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:22.000
At least once a year, you got your mom to take you out there.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:25.000
It was one of the big events of the summer.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.000
What else would that have been?

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.000
Well, Niagara sort of half-moving it will travel.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:35.000
There was a theater, I think, in Bethesda,

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.000
where there was a picket line,

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:42.000
and I think we went as far as Haggertown, maybe.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:45.000
And out toward the eastern shore.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:49.000
And then with the JLN and Rock Hills South Carolina,

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:52.000
the call went out to come down and join them.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.000
Did you go?

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:58.000
Well, a bunch of us went down as sort of a weekend support thing.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:00.000
We did not go for the JLN.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
But we went down that way,

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:06.000
and I was in contact with Reverend C.A. Ivory,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:14.000
who was the adult college contact on that.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:22.000
It must have been your first active action in the deep south.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:25.000
That was the further south I'd been at that point.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.000
That differ.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:32.000
I mean, you were in Durham and Duke,

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:36.000
of course, a great progressive state of North Carolina.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:39.000
All engines of suburb of Washington,

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:41.000
not as reactionary.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:43.000
But now you're in Rock Hill.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
We're terrible things are going on.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:52.000
Well, I didn't feel terrified or anything.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:53.000
It was just the next step.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:57.000
And we were sort of an on-call movement,

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:01.000
a nag, and I may have been told

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:02.000
that I may have been,

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
I remember we visited jail-in,

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:07.000
where some folks were from DC.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
Frank Hut was in jail-in.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:13.000
He was reported for AFRO.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.000
Some of our group did get a,

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
some nag folks got arrested,

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
but did not stay there.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:23.000
The whole sentence.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:26.000
And I've heard that I was arrested,

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.000
but I think I was just,

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
I may have, I don't even remember being booked.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:31.000
I may have been booked,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:34.000
but I think it may have been more of a protective custody.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.000
We're taking you in type of thing.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.000
There was never any trial of what have you.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:45.000
Were there many points on this particular venture?

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
Now, I don't remember it racially.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
I would say it was predominantly black.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:51.000
Nag was predominantly black.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.000
So maybe they were singling you out

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:54.000
because they didn't want you to.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.000
NAG cohort may have been in on that.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:00.000
But if we were, we were picketing.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:06.000
And I think things were on the rough side.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:09.000
They may have been justified as protective custody.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.000
I just don't remember.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:16.000
Was Carmichael in?

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:19.000
I don't remember Carmichael then.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.000
So are you still working on the hill while you're doing all this?

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.000
You were, you know, and you were just sort of...

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:28.000
Now, the thing that's interesting to me about Rock Hill,

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
and this diverges a little bit from me,

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
but to draw the connection,

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:37.000
the Diane Nash Nash,

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
or the Nashville movement,

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:42.000
is one of the people who had answered the call.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:47.000
And this was like in February or something,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.000
January, February, I'd have to check.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
But in December,

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
the Supreme Court had made a ruling

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:57.000
on the facilities in interstate commerce.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
Diane Nash was in the jail end,

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
stayed the sentence.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:05.000
Tom Gaither was down there from court,

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:09.000
leaving Rock Hill after the jail end.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:11.000
Tom and I think,

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
carry on a Greyhound bus,

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:17.000
started talking about doing something to test

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
the Supreme Court ruling.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:22.000
And the whole idea of the Freedom Ride was formed,

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:26.000
Snick had its April meeting in Charlotte,

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:29.000
and referred back to the Supreme Court decision

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:32.000
and called for students to test the ruling.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:35.000
Not necessarily get arrested in a strange town,

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:37.000
but see if it's being enforced.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:41.000
Well, you had this Snick thing that came out in April.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.000
Diane Nash had just been in the jail end,

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:49.000
so when all hell broke loose in May in Alabama,

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
things were primed from two directions for the student movement.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
The kids who had been in the deep south,

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:58.000
in the south with the sit-ins,

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
to continue.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:05.000
It was just like you had been priming it.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:08.000
Well, the Freedom Ride started in Washington.

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:09.000
Started in Washington.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.000
Were you aware of what was going on?

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
Oh, yeah.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.000
Paul Dietrichs, who was one of our leaders,

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:21.000
it was the restaurant that he was manager at,

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:25.000
the Chinese restaurant, really, had the last supper.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:29.000
Henry "Hank" Thomas was one of the original 13,

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:32.000
and of course,

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:34.000
John Lewis was involved in this,

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
so he was a Snick person,

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.000
so we were well aware of it.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.000
So when the bus was burned in Aniston,

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:47.000
and there was the picture of Hank standing outside the burning bus,

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:53.000
the nag was just as quick out of the shoot as Nashville,

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:57.000
but Nashville was closer to Alabama.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:00.000
So they got there first,

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.000
but I mean three of our guys left right away.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:07.000
Paul, John Moody, and NAG cohort,

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:10.000
but by the time they could get down there,

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
without all the interstates,

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:15.000
things had moved to Montgomery,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:21.000
and they were trapped in that church that was surrounded by everyone,

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.000
and the tear gas and all that,

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.000
and Paul called me from the basement of the church

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
when you had like a minute or two to call.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:32.000
He knew I was in an efficiency apartment,

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
and the phone was very close to the bed.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.000
That was better to call that,

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.000
than say a dormitory and Howard,

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
for you'd have to go wandering around,

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
and your two minutes would be up,

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
and it was just that we're trapped in the church.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:47.000
I can't talk, but send more people.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:50.000
And we started sending more.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:55.000
So on May 4, 1961,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
13 freedom writers,

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:00.000
Lee Washington, on a bus tour of this south,

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:03.000
to test the Supreme Court really.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:06.000
A month later, you were arrested in Jackson, Mississippi,

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:08.000
you were just talking about

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.000
you're getting the phone call from the church in Montgomery

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:14.000
that was surrounded, saying, send more people.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.000
What happened next?

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:20.000
Well, we started trying to get folks from NAG

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:24.000
see who could go and filter them in two or three at a time.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:29.000
Actually, NAG ended up sending second only to NAG Phil,

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.000
and numbers of the students,

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.000
and the southern student movements,

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:37.000
so we were right there just further.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:40.000
So by the time I went,

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:43.000
things had gotten very routine.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:46.000
The Kennedys had struck their bargain with the power structure.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:49.000
You came into Jackson.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:51.000
Talk about what was the bargain, this thing?

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:56.000
The deal was the Kennedys didn't like the bad PR worldwide,

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:00.000
and Kennedy and Kreechef were going to be dosy-dowing,

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:03.000
and it was bad press.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.000
They wanted that stopped.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:11.000
Mississippi wanted to arrest those outside agitators.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:16.000
So Mississippi agreed there would be no violence like Alabama,

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:19.000
but they could arrest people on a local charge.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
So we were charged with breach of peace,

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:26.000
meaning we made other people feel like beating us up.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:30.000
So you got off the train, you got off the bus,

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.000
whatever, Jackson MS Police Captain J.L. Ray would arrest you.

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:37.000
You all move on, move out, did you hear me?

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:40.000
You're going to do it, you're under arrest,

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.000
and then you got the Patty Wagon.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:47.000
It had gotten down scripted by the time I got down there.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
How did you get there?

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:52.000
We flew to New Orleans, a group of naggers,

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:55.000
NAG Freedom Rider cohort and NAG Freedom Rider cohort,

00:41:55.000 --> 00:42:00.000
Gwen Green, NAG Freedom Rider cohort, those two later married,

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:05.000
and the spite of what Stokely wanted to do.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:11.000
NAG Freedom Rider cohort and a couple more joined us from other places.

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:14.000
In New Orleans we had a day or so of orientation,

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:16.000
not real training as I remember,

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:19.000
because we were already trained,

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:25.000
and got the train tickets and got off in Jackson,

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:28.000
and didn't try to get off anywhere else.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:33.000
There were police, there were maybe a few rough looking characters

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:37.000
on the platform, but that's probably true on any given day,

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:41.000
on the train platforms,

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:45.000
and there were some white college students in the car

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:48.000
who made a couple little remarks,

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:50.000
but you know, nothing you would have...

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.000
You got off the train and you walked in.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:56.000
And Jackson, after pretty much an uneventful ride,

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:59.000
walked into the train station,

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:03.000
did that little dosido with Jackson MS Police Captain J.L. Ray,

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:06.000
walked out to the patty wagon, now what can...

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:09.000
Now why were you going to the Negro side,

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
or how were you a red...

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:13.000
I think we were all in the white side,

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:17.000
but as a group, black and white together.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:21.000
So you were breaching the piece just as anyone else was?

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:22.000
Yeah, we were making...

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:25.000
whoever might be hanging out waiting for us,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:28.000
feel like hitting us.

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.000
But when we got to the city jail,

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
what has really struck me,

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:36.000
is it was sort of a big step down from the patty wagon,

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:39.000
and I was looking like this sweet young thing,

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:43.000
and the police officer just automatically reached out to help me down.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:47.000
Now he would not have done this if I were black, I know that.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:48.000
But...

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
You thought you were maimed?

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:53.000
We don't want anything to happen to y'all,

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:57.000
and then it was like he was struck by lightning.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
Oh my God, what am I doing?

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:02.000
And jerked his hand back.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:07.000
But what has struck with me that his first instinct was good.

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.000
Wouldn't have been good if I were black,

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:13.000
but he showed a definite humanity there.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:16.000
Yeah, and that sort of gave me faith

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:19.000
that it was all going to be okay in the end.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:22.000
Which I mentioned when the freedom writers were back

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:26.000
and treated the brunch at the governor's mansion.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:32.000
I told that story and wanted to thank those

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.000
who would help to make that true,

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:37.000
as we had the black chief of police,

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.000
the black head of the state highway patrol,

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:42.000
you know, all of them, etc., etc.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.000
And Haley Barber,

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:48.000
who did more than he's still only credited with.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:53.000
So you were taken to the Kinds County Jail?

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:56.000
Now we were taken to the city jail for us.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:59.000
It was my lovely mug shot.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:00.000
And...

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:01.000
Famous photo?

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:02.000
Now a famous photo.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
And for this?

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:07.000
I think I look sort of calmer in that,

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:10.000
but then most of the freedom writers, women, white women,

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:13.000
because I was within my own culture.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:16.000
I was right, you're the book of photographs of all of them.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.000
You look like...

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.000
You might be your book photo.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:22.000
Yeah, but I was at home,

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:25.000
whereas all these folks that came from the north

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
were going into a war zone in their mind,

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:31.000
the hostile territory,

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:34.000
and they didn't feel one bit comfortable.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:36.000
Furthermore, they couldn't understand the language,

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.000
you know what the food was.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
I had to explain that.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:42.000
Yes, you were the ambassador.

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:46.000
But we were in the city jail until our trial.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:47.000
How long was that?

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:49.000
Oh, that just took a few minutes.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:52.000
I don't even know, I don't remember if we were overnight or not.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:57.000
But the trial was scripted, literally.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:02.000
And then we were taken over to the county jail.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:05.000
And that, because all these cells were segregated

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:09.000
and the women's cell, white women's cell,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:12.000
where I was, before we were taken to parchment,

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:16.000
it had gotten so crowded that if we don't count the space

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:19.000
taken up by the shower stall or the bunks,

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:23.000
we had less than three square feet of floor space per person.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:26.000
Now, we had people sleeping under the bunks,

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:30.000
doubling up one person curled up in the shower stall,

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:33.000
and it dripped all night.

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:37.000
But they needed bigger facilities.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:43.000
But I felt so culturally isolated from all these Yankee girls

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:49.000
that I had more culturally in common with the black girls

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:52.000
and the next cell who were southerners.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:58.000
We knew about grits, black eyed peas.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:05.000
And years later, one of my cellmates that I've become good friends with

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:09.000
to happen in Minnesota, she's the one who wants to go to Ireland

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:12.000
and visit her father's home country.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:17.000
Her main memory of me is sitting over by the wall

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:22.000
where I could talk to the black girls that I was so,

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:26.000
I was culturally and just separate from the white girls

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:29.000
from New York and California and such.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:34.000
Did you have any visitors while you were in Jackson?

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:37.000
Well, the lawyers got by a few times.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
Women power unlimited.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.000
Talk about that.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.000
Clarke Reed College, Harvard, that's a group that people should know more about.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:46.000
They don't get the credit they should.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:49.000
It was a group of, as I understand it,

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.000
basically black church women,

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:56.000
but also some white church women working on almost a cell basis,

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:58.000
at least in the white community,

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:03.000
where nobody knew but one other person in another cell.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:06.000
To support the freedom writers,

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:09.000
raise money, do the attorney,

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
and get us things we needed,

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:16.000
and we could get a lot of things in the jail then.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.000
We literally made out of a list, you know,

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:21.000
shower shoes, t-shirts.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:25.000
We got postage stamps, paper,

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:28.000
sanitary products, toothbrushes,

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.000
anything we might need.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:34.000
They got the money to get it for us.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
And got delivered to the cell.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:39.000
I finally gave my shower shoes to the

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:42.000
Old State Capitol Museum,

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:46.000
where they displayed them until the Katrina came through.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.000
And then after we got out of jail,

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:52.000
because people, it was filled the jails,

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:55.000
but with a six-month sentence that a lot of folks got,

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:58.000
you didn't want to spend six months at parchment.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
So you had 39 days to bail.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
But after you got out, then you got,

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:05.000
they arranged, you know, showers,

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
homes you could stay in overnight,

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
get a shower, get clean clothes.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:12.000
I got clothes given to me when I got out,

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:15.000
because you basically had to close on your back,

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:18.000
you'd warn me you got arrested.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:21.000
So you weren't prepared,

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.000
you didn't have a bag with you or anything,

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
when you came into...

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:28.000
Just had a little overnight case of stuff,

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:31.000
which you had to turn over at parchment

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
and they rifled through,

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.000
and so you might not get back everything.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
Often you had a change of clothes in it,

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:42.000
but what you had when you got out of jail was a little iffy.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
But, you know, a good hot meal,

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:47.000
a nice, soft bed, a shower,

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:50.000
shampoo, all these good things,

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:54.000
the women power unlimited organized on an ongoing day.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
The founder of the Clarie Collins Harvey,

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:02.000
ran out one of the leading funeral bars in this.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Quite an amazing woman.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:08.000
You probably know a lot more about women power unlimited than I do.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:11.000
Well, the daughter of the investor Simpson,

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:16.000
the Morris, has written a book like manuscript

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
on women power that I read.

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:19.000
So yes, I do.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
Oh, I hope that gets to be a book.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
I would love to know more.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:26.000
Because it's, again,

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:29.000
focus is away from the local people

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:32.000
and all the people coming in from the outside

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:34.000
but the locals were active.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:38.000
I met on a trip somewhere in the Arctic.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:41.000
I would say probably off Bath and Island on a ship,

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
some women from Jackson.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:46.000
Just by chance, it was open seating for the meals

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:48.000
and was sad and oh, where are you from?

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
And I'd been a miss.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:54.000
Oh, where in Mississippi in a Tugaloo?

00:50:54.000 --> 00:51:00.000
And did I know anything about the Civil Rights Movement?

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:03.000
And they said, yeah.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:07.000
But these two elderly women were saying that back in that time

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:12.000
they kept telling the people that their church

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.000
that these folks are not violent,

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:16.000
they're not really breaking the law.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:19.000
They were very supportive verbally

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:22.000
and how much they may have done under the cover, I don't know.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:27.000
But it was so nice for them to hear

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:30.000
that what they had been saying was true.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:34.000
That we weren't all a pack of wild eye communists.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:36.000
I was invited over for tea sometimes

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.000
when I was passing through Jackson and took him up on it.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:43.000
But this was, people coming out of the woodwork years later.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:47.000
And of course, the newspapers ahead of them press.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
Oh, my, my.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
Did you read the Clarion Ledger and Daily News

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
when you were in jail?

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:56.000
Sometimes we got that in Heinz County.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:03.000
The trustees would take care of this that way.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
Do you remember your trial at all?

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.000
It was a quick one wasn't it?

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:11.000
Very quick and like I say, it was literally scripted.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:17.000
And I got two months, two months suspended, $200 fine.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:19.000
They kept upping it.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.000
And I was sort of at the medium level.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:27.000
Then it, before long, it was up to $600, $500, which was the max.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:31.000
And so, what were you,

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:34.000
were you thinking, parchment kind of pantry is one of the most notorious,

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:38.000
one of the most notorious reputations in the country?

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.000
It was a cotton plantation.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.000
It was isolated out in the middle of nowhere.

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:47.000
Not far from where Emmett Till was murdered, yep.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:51.000
So you're on your way up with their conversation?

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.000
What were you anticipating?

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
They weren't really telling us where we were going.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:59.000
There were rumors that we were going to be taken to parchment.

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:03.000
And I think the guys, some of the guys may already have been taken up.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:07.000
So you were so isolated even in the county jail,

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:11.000
as far as who you had communication with.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
How long were you in the county jail?

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:14.000
A couple weeks.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:15.000
Captain Diary.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
He didn't in my skirt.

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
Still have it.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:26.000
But when they actually took us, they didn't say where we were going.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:32.000
We were loaded into the back of, I guess it was a paddy wagon or truck,

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:35.000
like paddy wagon thing.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:41.000
And taken up, now I knew just intellectually I'd heard of parchment

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:48.000
that it was bad, but the full horror of it had not reached northern Virginia.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:51.000
And goalily you heard more about.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:56.000
At least, up here.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:00.000
But the scary part of the ride,

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:03.000
aside from not knowing where you're going, some of the other girls

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:06.000
had heard more about parchment than I had,

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:10.000
was when the driver turned off the road.

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.000
And this was before interstates.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:13.000
This was the two lane.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:18.000
And he turned off, went back a bit where there was this house.

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:22.000
And these guys were coming and looking in on us.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.000
We didn't know what was going to happen.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.000
Some of us thought we'd get killed.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:28.000
In retrospect, he probably needed a pit stop.

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:31.000
He was making season the moment at a friend's house.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:34.000
But anything could have happened.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:41.000
And things like that did happen.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:42.000
Went through the gates?

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:45.000
Went through the gates.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
Basically stripped.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:52.000
They gave us the course black and white stripe skirts.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:57.000
And I think a t-shirt for a top and took our stuff and bagged it.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:00.000
Even gave most of it back at the end.

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:06.000
And then we had the vaginal exam, which was nasty.

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:09.000
One of my friends said,

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:14.000
thought that the woman who was doing it to us, who was matron,

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:19.000
probably, she seemed uncomfortable with it.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:24.000
One of the same person, good friends with now,

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:27.000
didn't remember this at all.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:30.000
Talked about it.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:33.000
But then when we talked about it,

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:38.000
she knew that the smell of lysol gave her the chills.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:42.000
This was a good 45 years after the fact.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:45.000
But she didn't remember.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:48.000
She didn't know why.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:51.000
She had completely blocked out the vaginal exam.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:57.000
But the smell just still got to her.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:00.000
So you're putting a segregated wing?

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:03.000
Well, the cells were segregated.

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:06.000
But it's this one cell block.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:09.000
So it's just one side of the wing.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:12.000
But it could be a white cell, a black cell, a black cell, a white cell.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:15.000
So it was a segregated white cell.

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:17.000
There were no guys around.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:20.000
But say two or three white girls would be in together.

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:25.000
But the next cell would be all black.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:27.000
So you had communication.

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:28.000
You had communication.

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:30.000
But you didn't see people.

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
You knew voices, perhaps.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:42.000
And actually it was at the Freedom Rider reunion thing

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:48.000
that I met this one woman, Helen Singleton, in California.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:51.000
And she remembered my voice and name.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.000
She had no idea what I looked like.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:56.000
And it was like, oh wow, this was a great moment.

00:56:56.000 --> 00:57:00.000
But if you, yeah, you would go down the cell block for a shower.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:06.000
But the matron would be on this between you and the other cell, the cells.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:08.000
And you would just zoom down it and back.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:17.000
So you didn't really get to see people and connect a face with a voice and name.

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:31.000
So we were in the cell block, not really having any mental image of the prison form beyond our cell block.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:34.000
We knew it was death row.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:37.000
But we didn't know exactly where the death chamber was.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
They cleaned out death row for you.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:40.000
Yeah, they cleaned out.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:43.000
And actually, what?

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:44.000
They just saved that.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:49.000
They cleaned out death row, emptied it out.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:52.000
And it was much cleaner.

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:54.000
And the food was a lot better.

00:57:54.000 --> 00:58:00.000
And we had a lot more room per cell per person than we had in Heinz County.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.000
The barter was a step up.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:08.000
And physically it was a step up.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:15.000
But in Heinz County, if you could scream bloody murder or you could even sing as a group,

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:22.000
and they could hear you on the streets of Jackson, here as they pointed out to us,

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:27.000
and no reporters are going to get you.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:31.000
So the psychological component, after you go through this little exam,

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:37.000
and then you're in complete isolation and at their mercy, really played on a lot of minds.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:43.000
What was the typical day like in Parksville?

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:44.000
You woke up?

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:47.000
You woke up, you got breakfast, you had it.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:50.000
What was breakfast?

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.000
Don't remember anything noteworthy.

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:58.000
Grits, fat back, that type of thing.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:03.000
The food to me was unremarkable, but it was southern.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:05.000
So it was normal.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:10.000
We had fried chicken and lemonade for the 4th of July.

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:14.000
And Mississippi had not been celebrating the 4th of July for that long,

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
because Vicksburg had fallen on the 4th.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:21.000
Plus the fireworks never got down there in time anyway, leading to a great new year.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:32.000
But I was surprised that they would do something special for the 4th of July, especially for us.

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
We got coffee.

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.000
That's where I took up drinking coffee.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:40.000
What did you do with all your spare time during the day?

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:43.000
Well we had some quiet times, we had reading.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:45.000
You could get books.

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:47.000
New Testament?

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:48.000
No, that was it.

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:52.000
And that led to some fussing by the Jewish girls.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:58.000
And I think they got Old Testament set on that one.

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.000
Made decks of cards out of it.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:06.000
We could get mail, censored mail once a week, on a good week, and send that a letter.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:16.000
So we could use the envelopes and things from our mail to make a deck of cards in place all of it here.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:26.000
In fact, my deck of cards I've forgotten about, but it's at the American History Museum.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:32.000
What were your conversations like with the women and the other selves?

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:33.000
We would be getting news.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:38.000
If you had new folks come in, you get the world news and what have you.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:43.000
Maybe where they were from, where they went to school, just routine stuff.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:47.000
And then we would have lectures.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:49.000
People had expertise.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:53.000
One woman who was a Greek classics professor.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:58.000
And so we would have lectures, you know, college level lectures.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:05.000
So you're all sitting in cells and you have, you hear this voice that you can't see who is educating you.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:06.000
Yes.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:11.000
And somebody might know a language, this language or that language.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:16.000
And we would be having lectures in Swahili or French or whatever.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:20.000
And we'd have enforced, we'd have quiet time.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:22.000
And that was, this is quiet time.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:28.000
This is quiet time, you know, for a while, somebody would announce it.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:30.000
But we had exercise time.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:33.000
Somebody is counting out one, two, three, four.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:39.000
You know, and you'd be doing whatever exercise was announced.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:43.000
How much time did you have outside of your cell?

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.000
Well, I think once, maybe just twice a week you got a shower.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:50.000
Walk down quick shower and back.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:51.000
You're in toilets in your cell.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:53.000
I had toilets in a wash basin.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:54.000
Now the side.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:02:07.000
The cell was, I think it was maybe seven or eight feet long.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:09.000
Eight might be a stretch.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:12.000
And maybe six feet across.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:18.000
I figured it out once that it was a little bit smaller than the cell that Nelson Mandela spent years in.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:23.000
And we had up to three or four people in it, but usually two.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:28.000
You put this mattresses unless they got, you know, you aggravated the jailers by singing

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.000
and they could take your mattresses away.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:32.000
Did they do that? I knew that. They did that for the guy.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:33.000
Oh, they did it. Yeah.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:36.000
And the, there were bunks.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:43.000
And it was like a metal sheet with these little holes in it, which made it, you know, softer.

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:49.000
But it could be a little uncomfortable without the mattress and cold.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:50.000
Did you sing a lot?

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:51.000
Oh, yeah.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:52.000
They'd be singing.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:55.000
Now those Yankees didn't know how to sing.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:01.000
You know, they had sort of a union singing, whereas we had a spiritual singing in the South.

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:03.000
Didn't know how to clap either.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:04.000
Oh, heavens no.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:08.000
No, no, no. They're clapping was way off.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:12.000
And I can't carry a tune in the bucket, but I knew they didn't know how to sing.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:19.000
Now the other time we had, well, the lawyer could come once a week and he'd work down the cell block,

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:23.000
but always accompanied by somebody from the prison.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:25.000
It varied.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:30.000
It varied who came up, but you had Jack H. Young Sr and Carsie Hall.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:37.000
I think our just brought out local black lawyers.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:44.000
I don't think that you had to be a member of whatever the Mississippi bar.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:50.000
You couldn't have William Kunstler coming down because they weren't recognized.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:59.000
And then there was about a two hour window or maybe three hours once a week that a religious person could come.

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:01.000
What about Rabbi Nusbaum?

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:02.000
Yeah, we're getting to him.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:03.000
Okay.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
Rabbi Nusbaum is truly one of my heroes.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:16.000
He would drive up from Jackson where the Jewish community was not, you know, smiled upon by the power structure every week faithfully.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:24.000
And I figured the only reason he was not killed on one of those roads is that the power structure had given the word don't kill him.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:28.000
But, you know, you could have had a rogue clansman any day, take him out.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:32.000
He came up faithfully every week and they come down.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:43.000
They call out, want to pray with the Rabbi, call out your cell number and then they push a little button to open up your gate and you go up.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:53.000
And by the time this has happened a few times, I remember it as we were standing more or less in a circle.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:05:03.000
No, at first we may have been sitting on benches, but we'd be gathered around and he would start to pray in Hebrew.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:13.000
And it would sort of lull off the wardens and all and then he'd be slipping in little bits of news, world news.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:18.000
And then he'd switch back to Hebrew and after a while it slipped in a little more news.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:38.000
And then he would get to see each of us individually for a couple seconds and maybe your mother says your aunt is sick or you'd say, tell my mother, daddy don't, he'd send out a form letter to all the families with a note at the bottom to keep this communication secret or it may have to stop.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:51.000
And that was our big thrill of the week. Now one week a couple of Catholic guys showed up and I think there were seminarians.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:53.000
Yes, for you, right?

01:05:53.000 --> 01:06:07.000
No, they came to minister to us and you could pick between the Rabbi and the seminarians and you know I grew up in a Jewish community or a lot of Jews, Jewish playmates and a man of God.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:18.000
A man of God is a man of God. I wasn't going to be picky, but if we had a Christian, I would prefer the Christian, even though I wasn't Catholic, but there were no Presbyterians.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:22.000
So I went to pray with the Catholics.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:35.000
Now we had girls from Jewish families who were not observant of practicing or whatever and they had not gone to see the Rabbi because they thought that would be sort of hypocritical of them.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:47.000
Man, some of them were down on me for deserting the Rabbi and going with the Catholics. I really heard about it. They didn't have anything else to stress over, but I had betrayed the Rabbi.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:56.000
But they didn't go to pray with. But the Rabbi and I were friends after I got out and he was out at two glibblos a lot.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:07.000
When we first got in, came into Jackson in 1967. There were two clan bombings. We heard the first was at the synagogue. The second was at Rabbi Perry Nussbaum.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:13.000
That was six years later. I just don't sit like I should.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:20.000
No, you just did a terrible job of sitting here, but the talking is all right. We'll let it slide.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:26.000
Thank you. You can edit that part out.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:31.000
No, that's my little cameo.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:40.000
Was there any acts of violence committed against you or anyone that you do in Richmond?

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:50.000
There was a girl who needed some medicine and they wouldn't give it to her. We'll call the doctor and we banged and protest on that one.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:08:05.000
But as far as knocking us around, no. Now the guys I've heard had a different story. But not that I knew of them.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:10.000
Most people bailed out after 39 days. You didn't why?

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:22.000
Well, I didn't need to. I had a two month sentence which covered and then I had the $200 fine which every additional day counted $3 against.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:31.000
And a free room and board for the summer. I had been accepted at Tugelou College before the Freedom Rides.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:45.000
And I figured I'm in Mississippi and the idea was fill the jails and make it so inconvenient for the Great and sovereign state and the feds that the law would be a bait.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:49.000
So you saw a lot of people come and go when you were there.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:52.000
I heard a lot of people come and go.

01:08:52.000 --> 01:09:00.000
Did you get new cell mates when your cell mates were?

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:09.000
Yeah. We get new cell mates and sometimes if there was a big influx there might be three and I've heard up to four women in one cell.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:13.000
And just put the extra mattresses under the cot.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:17.000
So you got out what the end of August, early September?

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:29.000
Because the rabbi, I remember him telling us that next week I won't be here because it's a holy day and I have to be with my congregation.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:32.000
It must have been the new year.

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:39.000
And I got out that week. School started it, you know, not the first of September.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:46.000
So if we went back and checked the calendar for that year we could figure it out but paid off the rest of it.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:55.000
Have you ever set foot on Chugelou's campus before you came to talk about your coming out and what you experienced?

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:04.000
Well, I came out and you could only leave parchment on one day of the week, whichever it fell.

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:11.000
I came out and went to the Freedom House on Rose Street in Jackson.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:24.000
And I was there for a couple days before in Chugelou but this is where I got, you know, clothes provided by women power and limited and freshened up and saw some old friends at the Freedom House.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:37.000
Then went out to Chugelou and I had applied to Chugelou because in reaction to when Charlayne Hunter-Gault got and Hamilton E. Holmes had gone to Georgia and been driven off with riots and tear gas.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:47.000
In the picture of Charlene clutching her Madonna, I just spoke to me and my family was from Georgia and some relatives could have been in the crowd.

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:55.000
So I had felt that this school integration was real, it had to be a two-way street and I would apply it historically.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:07.000
Like colleges and, okay, they may not want me but I will reach out and Chugelou accepted me.

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:16.000
Somebody in Snick suggested I applied to Chugelou because there have been no student movement there yet and be a good for you to be there.

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:19.000
There had been the Chugelou 9.

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:21.000
Not when I applied.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:24.000
Okay, but the library said in that had occurred.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:31.000
You know, after I applied, no, the library said in and Freedom Rights broke loose so it was, Mississippi was central.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:36.000
You seek out Chugelou because of this reputation as being a liberal black college.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:38.000
No, just being black and...

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:41.000
Did you apply elsewhere other than Chugelou?

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:45.000
Somewhere in Tennessee and I forget where else but probably three or four.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:48.000
I wanted a school that was accredited.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:51.000
Did you hear from the other school?

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.000
I don't think so.

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:58.000
But on the other hand, I didn't get all my mail after I left on the Freedom Ride.

01:11:58.000 --> 01:12:05.000
But Chugelou had figured that it was, it's charter, it was older than the segregation laws.

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:11.000
It was like grandfathered and its financial support was from the North.

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:17.000
And occasionally you had the children of White faculty who had been attending classes there.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:19.000
I'd heard that they'd been.

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:23.000
So it was not that you were, as Asalbans said, the first white student at Chugelou.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:32.000
No, there had been white faculty students taking a course or two but I don't think regularly and roll full time.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:36.000
Talk about those first days and two, there's one more on this one.

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:38.000
Okay.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:44.000
Okay, well in the meantime Charlotte Phillips, I think was from Pennsylvania.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:47.000
White girl had applied and been accepted.

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:52.000
She was having her semester abroad thing.

01:12:52.000 --> 01:13:01.000
And the first few days, well the first semester, people couldn't tell us apart too well.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:03.000
All look alike.

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:05.000
Yeah, we all looked alike.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:07.000
About the same height, same size, long hair.

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:09.000
Her hair was a little darker than mine.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:11.000
But you know, we looked alike.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:14.000
So that led to some interesting and confusing moments.

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:15.000
No, that was not me.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:19.000
You saw walking back into the woods with that guy.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:24.000
My room made, so a four of us in one room.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:26.000
And they...

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:29.000
What do I remember when you were in the Galloway?

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:31.000
When was that Galloway?

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:32.000
Yeah.

01:13:32.000 --> 01:13:35.000
And they didn't know they were getting a white room made.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:38.000
I was asleep on the bed and that was a little surprising.

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:40.000
But it was fine.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:47.000
The most interesting or amusing moment was that first night and the word had not spread.

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:53.000
They had bathrooms down the hall.

01:13:53.000 --> 01:14:00.000
And I was tiptoeing down the hall and a little flimsy outfit.

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:07.000
And a girl was tiptoeing in the other direction and saw me and thought I was a ghost and screamed.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:09.000
But we got out.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:11.000
True story, true story.

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:14.000
It was a pink and white flowery little, what we called shorties.

01:14:14.000 --> 01:14:21.000
And I must have looked otherworldly in more ways than one.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:26.000
But there was no unpleasantness from other students.

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:27.000
Were curious.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:32.000
There was some curiosity and there was sort of a wait and see.

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:38.000
But people were friendly enough.

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:48.000
And the freedom writers had already been back in August when they were called back for court appearance to set trial dates.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:51.000
Those who had bailed.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:15:00.000
And so the idea of white students on the campus was not breaking news.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:05.000
The faculty was strongly white, probably a little more than 50-50.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:14.000
And there had been these social science forums where white students would come out and white citizens of Jackson that wanted to come out to Tugaloo.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:23.000
Arens Borenskies down in the lab, which was a glorified cellar.

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:30.000
An amazing book needs to be written about that place.

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:37.000
But the idea of white's on campus, including students, was not altogether new.

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:41.000
But a full time enrolled living in the dormitory.

01:15:41.000 --> 01:15:43.000
This was new.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:16:00.000
And one girl in the A.K.A. said to me, well, I wasn't sure about you at first, but then I saw you had to study just as hard as we did over in the library.

01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:09.000
So I think, particularly when I came back the second year, I was in.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:15.000
I was still involved with SNCC and Core Down a little part time.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:21.000
What were you doing that academic year, 61-62, in terms of movement activity?

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:26.000
Should be pointed out that Tugaloo was about six miles north of downtown Jackson.

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:29.000
So it was somewhat isolated at the time.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:35.000
To the extent we had a movement on campus, I was involved in that.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:40.000
I mean, whatever was happening, I was also involved in other campus activities.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:45.000
It wasn't just movement.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:56.000
But I would, I guess, on weekends, or when I could go down, they had the SNCC Core Office down on Lynch Street.

01:16:56.000 --> 01:17:00.000
So from Medusa Office, and I would do Secretary-O work down there.

01:17:00.000 --> 01:17:07.000
It was generally, well, white women with SNCC did not go into the Delta, did not go outside of Jackson.

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:14.000
It would be counterproductive to go get us all killed, which made sense to me.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:20.000
But it kept that movement connection.

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:24.000
And had to get my lessons out. God helped me with math and science.

01:17:24.000 --> 01:17:26.000
What were your majoring in?

01:17:26.000 --> 01:17:28.000
Anything that avoided math and science.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:35.000
I thought it was going to be sociology, but it ended up being history because of that three hours of statistics.

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:38.000
Oh, yes, yes.

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:42.000
So I would have had a double major except for that three hours.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:46.000
Remember any of your history professors?

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:50.000
Now that you're asking me right off the top.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:54.000
I remember them, and I can picture them, but I can't call their name right now.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:56.000
Oct�man, maybe.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:17:58.000
Where they went?

01:17:58.000 --> 01:18:02.000
White, yeah.

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:10.000
So the summer of between your first and second year or two, what did you do then?

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:12.000
Did you stay in Mississippi or?

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:17.000
I think you asked me to dig back off or far in the, in the press.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:25.000
I think I stayed in Mississippi and worked in this SNCC core office.

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:31.000
Well, the 62-63 thing we're really heating up.

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:35.000
SNCC had moved up into the Delta.

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:41.000
And some students there like Joyce Ladner Ladner and Joyce Ladner Ladner were commuting up there.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:49.000
A movement started on campus with the campus youth chapter of the NAACP.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:51.000
And that led to...

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:53.000
Now that was in Jackson, North Jackson.

01:18:53.000 --> 01:19:01.000
We had our nonviolent agitation association of college people in the ACP on campus.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:09.000
But Reverend Edwin King's back room became...

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:13.000
Reverend Edwin King was the white chaplain from Vicksburg.

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:17.000
And he was very strong on the movement.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:19.000
That's why he was there.

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:25.000
And the back bedroom which was accessible from the back porch was just sort of the movement room.

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:30.000
You could use it as a study hall, as wife, Jeannette King always had coffee brewing.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:33.000
It's sort of just outside the room.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:37.000
It was also the guest bedroom of William Kunstler was down.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:41.000
And I remember typing up...

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:43.000
I could type as fast as he could dictate.

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:51.000
So I was typing up legal documents as he was pacing around in his boxers shorts.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:55.000
And what is happening in 62 and what's happening in 63?

01:19:55.000 --> 01:19:59.000
I really could not tell you that whole...

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:03.000
Yeah, I'm an into the next year.

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:06.000
When John R. Salter Jr was there...

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:12.000
John R. Salter Jr was a political science professor in northern...

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:18.000
Well, western radical organizer professor.

01:20:18.000 --> 01:20:20.000
And he started the North Jackson...

01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:26.000
Or he was the adult sponsor of the North Jackson Youth Council of the NAACP.

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:28.000
And his...

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:30.000
I mean it's a small campus.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:32.000
His house was also a movement headquarters.

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:38.000
If you weren't over typing for a lawyer or hanging out or something at Ed's,

01:20:38.000 --> 01:20:42.000
you were over at John's stuffing envelopes for the boycott that got going.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:48.000
Were any black faculty involved in these activities?

01:20:48.000 --> 01:20:54.000
I don't remember precisely black faculty involvement,

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:58.000
but some of them were supportive, I feel.

01:20:58.000 --> 01:21:00.000
I couldn't call names unless I got out of your book.

01:21:00.000 --> 01:21:04.000
I think Michael Bryan has borrowed my yearbooks.

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:06.000
They keep passing around.

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:10.000
I asked because at least when we were there,

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:14.000
it was basically the white faculty who was the activist and the black faculty.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:18.000
They were doing other things in town,

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:22.000
but they did not have that kind of relationship with the students.

01:21:22.000 --> 01:21:26.000
They were not the people whose homes you gathered at for things.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:30.000
I remember in 1966 with the Meredith March,

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:36.000
it was Dean Branch's house that was turned into the big breakfast buffet

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:38.000
where I sat next to Marlon Brando.

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:40.000
Oh wow.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:42.000
That makes it...

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:44.000
You have to have trivia questions about yourself later in life.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:46.000
That's mine.

01:21:46.000 --> 01:21:50.000
And it was at Branch's house that they had the long meeting the night before,

01:21:50.000 --> 01:21:54.000
the final day of the March when they had the hatch out who was speaking in one order.

01:21:54.000 --> 01:21:56.000
I missed that part, but yeah.

01:21:56.000 --> 01:22:04.000
So back to the North Jackson Youth Council.

01:22:04.000 --> 01:22:10.000
John R. Salter Jr is the adult advisor and what sort of actions were...

01:22:10.000 --> 01:22:12.000
Were you involved at this level?

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:14.000
I was not involved.

01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:18.000
Well, I would be at his house a fair amount,

01:22:18.000 --> 01:22:21.000
but I was not going to the North Jackson meetings.

01:22:21.000 --> 01:22:23.000
I wasn't in North Jackson.

01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:27.000
I was with the NAACP agitation group out at Tougaloo.

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:31.000
And Joyce Ladner Ladner Ladner and I were co-chair of that.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:33.000
But we were supportive.

01:22:33.000 --> 01:22:35.000
We might be stuffing envelopes,

01:22:35.000 --> 01:22:37.000
but we weren't going to the meetings in Jackson.

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:39.000
We were back at campus studying,

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:41.000
because we were students first and foremost.

01:22:41.000 --> 01:22:45.000
Joyce Ladner Ladner told me once that she...

01:22:45.000 --> 01:22:47.000
Well, we'll get into this.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:49.000
A boycott was called.

01:22:49.000 --> 01:22:53.000
And Joyce Ladner Ladner was saying that she thought that was pretty neat.

01:22:53.000 --> 01:22:57.000
That she was more interested in what Smith was doing in the Delta view.

01:22:57.000 --> 01:23:05.000
That's possibly true.

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:07.000
There were different settings.

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:09.000
I don't remember Joyce Ladner Ladner on that point.

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:13.000
And we ended up being roommates and sorority sisters.

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:23.000
But I was getting the field reports from the Delta.

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:29.000
And I would take them and pull out gossip and news

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:31.000
and make a little...

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:33.000
I don't know, three or four pages,

01:23:33.000 --> 01:23:35.000
maybe two or three pages,

01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:37.000
staple together that would run off these carbon copies.

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:39.000
The North, let's see.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:41.000
The mix of sippy news.

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:47.000
Taken so that before the internet and cell phones,

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:51.000
people would send me a copy of their field report.

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:59.000
I would combine it and send it out so that everyone knew what everybody else was doing professionally and personally.

01:23:59.000 --> 01:24:01.000
Are there any copies of that film available?

01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:05.000
I would have loved it and come across that in my research.

01:24:05.000 --> 01:24:11.000
If there are, that would be in the stuff that I've given to the New Smithsonian Museum.

01:24:11.000 --> 01:24:19.000
I gave them the original of the field reports, which is some of the first SNCC reference to Panator Le Hamer, for instance.

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:23.000
But I have copy machine copies of that.

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:25.000
So you were very much aware of what was going on.

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:27.000
Oh yeah.

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:31.000
I couldn't go up into the Delta being white.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:33.000
But I certainly knew what was going on.

01:24:33.000 --> 01:24:37.000
And people for R&R would be down at Tuvalu,

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:41.000
or the Freedom House on Rose Street.

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:47.000
So I was, in some ways, more in touch with what was going on here and there than some of the people out there were.

01:24:47.000 --> 01:24:51.000
I remember we went up to Harding Carter's office, Reverend Edwin King and I,

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:53.000
and I forget who else was in the car once.

01:24:53.000 --> 01:24:57.000
And all my lands to openly go up into the Delta.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:24:59.000
I mean, that was a big event.

01:24:59.000 --> 01:25:01.000
Was this young Harding?

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:03.000
No, this was the old guy.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:05.000
The old Harding, no, I see it.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:07.000
I guess it was the old guy.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:08.000
Yeah.

01:25:08.000 --> 01:25:09.000
62?

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:11.000
Yeah, no, that was the old guy.

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:17.000
And then it was amazing years later to meet the grandson who had written the books on his travels.

01:25:17.000 --> 01:25:19.000
And I had traveled the same routes.

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:23.000
And I mean, the Seal River in Northern Manitoba and would both been there.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:25.000
Days apart.

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:27.000
You know, things like that.

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:28.000
I got it.

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:29.000
Sorry.

01:25:29.000 --> 01:25:30.000
Coffee time.

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:31.000
Coffee time.

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:32.000
Okay.

01:25:32.000 --> 01:25:33.000
We're rolling.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:39.000
In 1962, Jackson, Mississippi, the capital was a segregated city.

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:46.000
And the civil rights activists were trying to change all that.

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:56.000
And events unfolded that would have national and international significance in terms of what was going on.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:09.000
Talk a little bit about the boycott, your role, and the mood on campus in town in early 1963.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:13.000
Well, the boycott had been going, I think, over Christmas.

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:14.000
With the boycott downtown.

01:26:14.000 --> 01:26:16.000
The downtown merchants.

01:26:16.000 --> 01:26:20.000
And I guess building.

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:22.000
I was busy being a student.

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:23.000
Yeah.

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:31.000
But by spring, as I escalate a bit.

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:32.000
And demonstrations.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:35.000
There have been some picket demonstrations.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:46.000
And people arrested and students and faculty in the point now coming that need to step it up a little bit more.

01:26:46.000 --> 01:26:48.000
And apparently a sit-in was planned.

01:26:48.000 --> 01:26:51.000
I wasn't in on the planning of this.

01:26:51.000 --> 01:26:54.000
And I wasn't supposed to be part of that sit-in.

01:26:54.000 --> 01:26:57.000
There were going to be a...

01:26:57.000 --> 01:26:59.000
Her different versions of this.

01:26:59.000 --> 01:27:03.000
There was either going to be two demonstrations, complete entities of themselves.

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:07.000
Or the picket line down the street was to be a diversion.

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:09.000
To draw the police down there.

01:27:09.000 --> 01:27:11.000
That's what I'd always understood.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:14.000
And I was going to be a spotter.

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:18.000
And now a spotter is a person who just sort of blends into the crowd.

01:27:18.000 --> 01:27:24.000
Seize what's happening has some dimes in their pocket to call Medgar Evers' office and say,

01:27:24.000 --> 01:27:27.000
hey, they've been arrested, they've been beaten up or whatever.

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:28.000
Now Medgar Evers was...

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:34.000
Medgar Evers was the state's NAACP man, the long-time civil rights person before us.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:37.000
Outsiders got into the act.

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:40.000
The key figure in the state.

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:47.000
And so, Lois Chaffey, who was a dorm mother, they're not really much older than us.

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:51.000
And I were the spotters for the picket line.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:55.000
And we didn't think they were going to get arrested right away.

01:27:55.000 --> 01:27:58.000
And the solvers wife, Elgory, was in the picket line?

01:27:58.000 --> 01:28:02.000
I don't remember who was in it, to be honest.

01:28:02.000 --> 01:28:04.000
Was it an integrated...

01:28:04.000 --> 01:28:06.000
It was an integrated picket line.

01:28:06.000 --> 01:28:13.000
She may well have been in the Eddie O'Neill, the student body president, I think, was in it.

01:28:14.000 --> 01:28:18.000
We thought the police would come down and arrest them right away, and that would give time for

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:23.000
the people who are going to be sitting in down the wallworths to get into the store

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:27.000
and make their little approaches and get situated.

01:28:27.000 --> 01:28:30.000
But the picket line was arrested right away.

01:28:30.000 --> 01:28:33.000
And so here, Lois and I are, we're phoned in.

01:28:33.000 --> 01:28:37.000
And okay, now what are we going to do?

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:41.000
Let's go down to wallworth and see what's happening there.

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:45.000
And they didn't think the planners didn't think much would happen.

01:28:45.000 --> 01:28:48.000
Pretty much the same thing that they would be arrested in the same jail.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:51.000
They thought the people sitting as I understood it at the time.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:58.000
They thought the people sitting in would be arrested right away.

01:28:58.000 --> 01:29:04.000
And we would just be, the picket line would just be a diversion to give them time to get in

01:29:04.000 --> 01:29:07.000
and the police would come down there and arrest them.

01:29:07.000 --> 01:29:12.000
Well, the Supreme Court had a ruling the week before that the police could not

01:29:12.000 --> 01:29:17.000
of their own volition go into a store and make arrest.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:24.000
They had to be invited in by the store manager, the irony being that my name was on one of the cases

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:27.000
that had been consolidated for this coming out of Durham.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:32.000
And there were cases from other, I think, Linneco also was in on this.

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:34.000
I think everyone was your ass for that.

01:29:34.000 --> 01:29:36.000
Yes.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:43.000
Well, we got down to wallworth and this was, there was a crowd forming.

01:29:43.000 --> 01:29:48.000
It was sort of getting ugly and this was sort of noonish.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:52.000
The Central High School was just a couple blocks away, I think,

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:59.000
and students were coming up on their lunch hour because it was exam week and white students.

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:07.000
And I think some of this segregationist haunches, the sovereignty commission

01:30:07.000 --> 01:30:12.000
or whatever were sort of encouraging people to come up and come in the store.

01:30:12.000 --> 01:30:17.000
Well, Memphis, Norman got pulled.

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:20.000
There were three students from Tougaloo sitting down.

01:30:20.000 --> 01:30:25.000
Annie, Moody, Memphis, Norman and Pearlena Lewis.

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:29.000
And they were sitting together with Memphis in the middle.

01:30:29.000 --> 01:30:32.000
And he got pulled off the stool and stomped and kicked.

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:38.000
And that's a long story well known and carted off by the police along with the guy who was attacking him

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:42.000
who was a former policeman known for his brutality.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:44.000
That lifted two girls alone.

01:30:44.000 --> 01:30:47.000
They were pulled off their stool, struggled back.

01:30:47.000 --> 01:30:51.000
Things were getting more and more mob-signish.

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:53.000
And the police were nowhere to be seen?

01:30:53.000 --> 01:30:55.000
Oh, no, they were outside laughing.

01:30:55.000 --> 01:31:01.000
Reverend Edwin King was the white chaplain, was the spotter there, and talking with the police who,

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:08.000
oh, we can't go in, you know, the Supreme Court ruling, we have to obey it.

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:14.000
And I think it was probably Ed who suggested that I sit down with the girls,

01:31:14.000 --> 01:31:19.000
that it would be safer for me, because I was starting to be sort of spotted.

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:24.000
I think I may be called out to one of the girls that somebody had a knife.

01:31:24.000 --> 01:31:26.000
And it would be safer for me.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:30.000
You always say if you've got a solid barrier on one side of you,

01:31:30.000 --> 01:31:33.000
that limits how many directions they can come at you.

01:31:33.000 --> 01:31:36.000
And it would be good moral support for the two girls at the counter.

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:38.000
So I sat down.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:43.000
And then we got pulled off the stool again and I got up to them.

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:49.000
But we were able to get loose and get back to the counter, but not back to where Perlina was.

01:31:49.000 --> 01:31:51.000
And Lois sat with Perlina.

01:31:51.000 --> 01:31:58.000
So you had a black and white girl here, and Annie and I sat black and white girl here.

01:31:58.000 --> 01:32:05.000
And little people would bravo-do and do this and do that.

01:32:05.000 --> 01:32:08.000
Throw something at us, dump some ketchup, maybe.

01:32:08.000 --> 01:32:13.000
And then Ed has called back to Medgar's office.

01:32:13.000 --> 01:32:19.000
And Medgar wants to come down, but he's talked out of it because he'd be killed pretty much on site.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:21.000
But John comes down-

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:22.000
John R. Salter Jr.

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:25.000
John R. Salter Jr, the white professor, comes down.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:30.000
And he makes his way to where Annie and I are sitting.

01:32:30.000 --> 01:32:35.000
I think Walter Williams, who had been the student body president at Jackson State,

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:42.000
but expelled for supporting, I think the Tougaloo Nine sit-in library sit-in group.

01:32:42.000 --> 01:32:46.000
Well, things keep going.

01:32:46.000 --> 01:32:57.000
And there's Annie looking like a skunk with the white sugar on her head and me with all sorts of nice condiments and John R. Salter Jr,

01:32:57.000 --> 01:33:03.000
who really got the brunt of the attack because he was a guy.

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:09.000
And brass knuckles mixing blood with the mustard and things.

01:33:09.000 --> 01:33:12.000
That's called the mustard man by the press.

01:33:12.000 --> 01:33:19.000
Now the guys in sunglasses, as I understand it, were all FBI agents, cleverly disguised.

01:33:19.000 --> 01:33:24.000
But basically, it's high school students who are there.

01:33:24.000 --> 01:33:32.000
The reporter, a local guy, Fred Blackwell, was literally standing on the counter when he took this shot, as I understand it.

01:33:32.000 --> 01:33:38.000
I just want to interrupt. That is one of the most iconic photographs of the Civil Rights Movement,

01:33:38.000 --> 01:33:41.000
probably showing more than any other.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:46.000
And at the Kennedy Library in Massachusetts, it's huge blow-up.

01:33:46.000 --> 01:33:49.000
Oh, that's worth a trip to Massachusetts.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:56.000
More so than the Woolworth of the Greensboro sit-ins, I mean, this has become...

01:33:56.000 --> 01:33:58.000
This has become it.

01:33:58.000 --> 01:34:01.000
I think the Greensboro sit-in is nice and orderly.

01:34:01.000 --> 01:34:07.000
This one, you have a definite feel of violence, it's imminent.

01:34:07.000 --> 01:34:13.000
But there is no actual violence happening at the moment, the camera clicked.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:18.000
But it tells the story, and it's an integrated group.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:23.000
So it's good to use in books for children.

01:34:23.000 --> 01:34:24.000
Cut.

01:34:24.000 --> 01:34:26.000
Straight all the time.

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:28.000
Oh, no, that's what that works better that way.

01:34:28.000 --> 01:34:30.000
Okay, we're all set.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:37.000
Now, this picture is also the basis for a lot of illustrations for kids' books,

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:42.000
but something I've noticed very consistently in the illustrations.

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:47.000
The person that would be me is always black.

01:34:47.000 --> 01:34:52.000
Now, I understand they want it to look like a black movement, black students.

01:34:52.000 --> 01:34:56.000
But why doesn't John R. Salter Jr ever turn black?

01:34:56.000 --> 01:35:00.000
It always feels female.

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:03.000
I think there are several answers to this.

01:35:03.000 --> 01:35:06.000
I'm curious, what are your thoughts?

01:35:06.000 --> 01:35:12.000
The main thought I have, well, aside from they want it to look like a black movement,

01:35:12.000 --> 01:35:22.000
but why always me, rather than John, is it has to do with the old thing about protecting white women from the black men?

01:35:22.000 --> 01:35:24.000
And I may be reading too much into it.

01:35:24.000 --> 01:35:33.000
It may be coincidental, but I still sort of wonder what this says about our lingering racial attitudes.

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:35.000
Very interesting.

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:43.000
Could be quite out that the photograph there is a cover of a book that features the World War City and the Jackson Movement.

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:47.000
We shall not be moved by Michael O'Brien.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:50.000
Wonderful book.

01:35:50.000 --> 01:36:01.000
Here we've got not only the lunch counter one, but at the beginning with Memphis sitting with the two girls,

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:04.000
and Memphis being stopped.

01:36:04.000 --> 01:36:10.000
He was bleeding out of every opening in his head.

01:36:10.000 --> 01:36:13.000
Yeah, that's the photograph you don't see much of.

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:17.000
And that's where you really get the full effect of the violence.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:21.000
It's much better for kids books to show this one.

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:23.000
Yes.

01:36:23.000 --> 01:36:33.000
But I've talked to several reporters, probably all the reporters that were behind the counter and the cameraman or their descendants,

01:36:33.000 --> 01:36:41.000
and across the board this is the most frightening experience at a demonstration they had in the Civil Rights Movement.

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:50.000
And none of them were in Birmingham for the bus burning or the riots, but just for Mississippi.

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:52.000
And they got around.

01:36:52.000 --> 01:36:55.000
What was so particular horrifying to me?

01:36:55.000 --> 01:36:58.000
I mean, how long did this go on?

01:36:58.000 --> 01:37:00.000
I lost track of time.

01:37:00.000 --> 01:37:03.000
I think it's supposed to been about three hours or so.

01:37:03.000 --> 01:37:04.000
Three hours.

01:37:04.000 --> 01:37:10.000
If you could imagine what it would like to be there for that amount of time with the crowd apparently not in underpants.

01:37:10.000 --> 01:37:14.000
Completely out of control and the police laughing.

01:37:14.000 --> 01:37:17.000
You had been, you were a veteran of Sittins.

01:37:17.000 --> 01:37:18.000
This was something new for you.

01:37:18.000 --> 01:37:24.000
What were your thoughts, what were your feelings when your back was to these people and you didn't know what was coming?

01:37:24.000 --> 01:37:31.000
Of course you were safer with the back and I think we may have had a bit of a mirror at the lunch counters where you could see some of it.

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:36.000
But our conversation we kept it light, joking.

01:37:36.000 --> 01:37:45.000
Professor Salter gave us much too hard of exams, but it was a deliberate attempt to keep our spirits up.

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:49.000
And for me it was sort of like an out-of-body experience at some point.

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:52.000
I've heard this happens on the battlefield.

01:37:52.000 --> 01:38:00.000
Like the real me had left and was sort of like up there like a guardian angel, keeping an eye on things, looking out for me.

01:38:00.000 --> 01:38:05.000
And this was just a shell that was sitting at the counter.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:07.000
So it's protective.

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:13.000
Yeah, anything else that stands out in your mind about that particular damage could have been.

01:38:13.000 --> 01:38:27.000
Well our college president, when he heard about it, came down and worked it out negotiating that the police would give us safe passage once the store was closed.

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:30.000
The cars could be brought up to pick us up.

01:38:30.000 --> 01:38:40.000
The manager didn't want to close the store, but apparently his regional district man said to.

01:38:40.000 --> 01:38:48.000
But our college president did come down and get things worked out and actually sat at the counter.

01:38:48.000 --> 01:38:56.000
Now be it doubt a bit talking to the reporters, but he's the only college president who sat at a lunch counter where his students were.

01:38:56.000 --> 01:38:58.000
Got to give him credit there.

01:38:58.000 --> 01:39:04.000
I don't understand why the manager didn't close the store. I mean they were tearing it apart.

01:39:04.000 --> 01:39:08.000
Well I think it was when they were seriously tearing it apart.

01:39:08.000 --> 01:39:14.000
Because they'd used up all the stuff that was real handy and were going further and further into the store.

01:39:14.000 --> 01:39:18.000
They were at trades and things like that.

01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:21.000
Had to have been.

01:39:21.000 --> 01:39:24.000
I mainly remember the condiments coming at us.

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:26.000
Spray paint and stuff.

01:39:26.000 --> 01:39:31.000
Were you at all? You said you were pulled off with chair?

01:39:31.000 --> 01:39:43.000
I don't think I wasn't like slugged, you know pushed around yes instead of carried by the waste virtually to the store exit where the guy actually got arrested.

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:46.000
But I think.

01:39:46.000 --> 01:39:47.000
And then you went back.

01:39:47.000 --> 01:39:51.000
Oh of course. Where else was I going to go into the mob?

01:39:51.000 --> 01:39:55.000
That was the point. I'm a one that you stay at the counter.

01:39:55.000 --> 01:39:57.000
You try to shield each other.

01:39:57.000 --> 01:39:59.000
But literally if I were.

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:01.000
Went out of the store.

01:40:01.000 --> 01:40:04.000
The mob was forming outside.

01:40:04.000 --> 01:40:06.000
I could have been.

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:10.000
That would have been more dangerous than returning to the counter.

01:40:10.000 --> 01:40:13.000
And the press was there.

01:40:13.000 --> 01:40:15.000
So what happens you are.

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:19.000
Finally the store is cleared. You are let out.

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:21.000
The waiting car.

01:40:21.000 --> 01:40:22.000
Cars pull up.

01:40:22.000 --> 01:40:26.000
And they take us back to the black community to down near Megger's office.

01:40:26.000 --> 01:40:30.000
And the ladies were taken over to the beauty parlor across the street.

01:40:30.000 --> 01:40:33.000
And that's woman power unlimited type thing.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:36.000
We got all cleaned up over there.

01:40:36.000 --> 01:40:38.000
Was there a mass meeting that night?

01:40:38.000 --> 01:40:40.000
A mass meeting that night.

01:40:40.000 --> 01:40:42.000
And man it was packed.

01:40:42.000 --> 01:40:44.000
This was a chapel.

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:45.000
No this was.

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:46.000
The church.

01:40:46.000 --> 01:40:48.000
Yeah I forget the name of the church.

01:40:48.000 --> 01:40:53.000
But whatever the main meeting church was in the black community.

01:40:53.000 --> 01:40:59.000
And of course on campus is always a to-do too.

01:40:59.000 --> 01:41:03.000
But mainly that evening where we all got introduced.

01:41:03.000 --> 01:41:06.000
Cleaned up by then.

01:41:06.000 --> 01:41:09.000
Things start to happen rapidly in Dexon after that.

01:41:09.000 --> 01:41:14.000
The national NAACP which has been sort of on the sidelines.

01:41:14.000 --> 01:41:20.000
And it's been a long time since the last time we had a meeting.

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:23.000
And we realized that this is big news.

01:41:23.000 --> 01:41:26.000
The national office comes to town.

01:41:26.000 --> 01:41:28.000
Roy Wilkins gets himself arrested.

01:41:28.000 --> 01:41:33.000
And yet at the same time there is an effort on the part of the Kennedy administration.

01:41:33.000 --> 01:41:41.000
We know this from the records to get people out of the streets to arrange some sort of a compromise.

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:44.000
And we don't see anything like this happening in Dexon.

01:41:44.000 --> 01:41:47.000
How much of this were you aware of on campus?

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:53.000
That things that have been at White Heat were now sort of can't bring back.

01:41:53.000 --> 01:41:58.000
Well you see this was right at the end of the school year.

01:41:58.000 --> 01:42:01.000
And I left within a day or two.

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:06.000
And came back to Washington and worked in the March on Washington office all summer.

01:42:06.000 --> 01:42:12.000
I was mainly getting just whatever was in the Washington post.

01:42:12.000 --> 01:42:15.000
I think.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:17.000
So you weren't there?

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:20.000
I wasn't there.

01:42:20.000 --> 01:42:22.000
John Doar was amazing.

01:42:22.000 --> 01:42:25.000
Another hero.

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:33.000
Meagher's body was a funeral home up here and the lines were around the block to go and see him.

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:36.000
I've been buried at Arlington.

01:42:36.000 --> 01:42:42.000
I still have the black creep ribbon that they gave us to pin on our clothes or arm bands or whatever.

01:42:42.000 --> 01:42:53.000
We should probably mention that at the height of all this, Meagher ever was assassinated by a member of the White Citizens Council of Divery and Delegue Beckwith.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:43:02.000
And at the funeral there were demonstrations and that John Doar of the Justice Department was able to keep things from exploding into a full riot.

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:08.000
By this time you were back in Washington working on the March on Washington.

01:43:08.000 --> 01:43:14.000
Any more you want to say about the Jackson movement or should we move on to Washington?

01:43:14.000 --> 01:43:18.000
I can't really speak to the Jackson movement right then because I wasn't there.

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:26.000
I was here basically working in the press section at the March on Washington headquarters.

01:43:27.000 --> 01:43:34.000
And we certainly didn't assume that the March was going to come off or smoothly.

01:43:34.000 --> 01:43:38.000
The newspapers were full of stories of worries about riots.

01:43:38.000 --> 01:43:41.000
Merchants were boarding up their windows downtown.

01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:43.000
They were going to realize that now.

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:45.000
The American Nazi Party was right across the river.

01:43:45.000 --> 01:43:50.000
There was a real fear of violence in the city.

01:43:51.000 --> 01:44:02.000
Plus at the March office we figured it was also quite likely that the federal government would intervene and literally prevent the buses from rolling into Washington.

01:44:02.000 --> 01:44:07.000
So the fact that that took place was wonderful.

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:15.000
I was working in the press, tend up on the monument grounds and did not literally march until we got sort of bust up closer.

01:44:15.000 --> 01:44:18.000
But it had been an awful year.

01:44:18.000 --> 01:44:27.000
Not only did King write it but have his dream speech but he had written the letter from the Birmingham Jail that spring.

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:30.000
There had been the whole Birmingham scene.

01:44:30.000 --> 01:44:33.000
There had been the whole Jackson scene.

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:35.000
It was awful.

01:44:35.000 --> 01:44:37.000
And there were a few other things.

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:40.000
There were more demonstrations at some of them.

01:44:41.000 --> 01:44:45.000
And then to have the march come off gloriously.

01:44:45.000 --> 01:44:49.000
In spite of John Lewis being censored.

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:57.000
And then just over two weeks later the church in Birmingham was bombed and those girls killed.

01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:02.000
You came back didn't you from the March on Washington with King and the group?

01:45:02.000 --> 01:45:06.000
Yeah, Ed and Annie and I came back with the King.

01:45:06.000 --> 01:45:11.000
This is by the way and Moody who wrote the book Coming of Ages Mississippi.

01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:12.000
Yes.

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:21.000
And we camped in a national park I think along the Blue Ridge or Shannando a national park.

01:45:21.000 --> 01:45:30.000
And we came out of the shower room together we got quite the looking over.

01:45:30.000 --> 01:45:37.000
We got back and went to school and then there was a church bombing.

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:43.000
So a van load of us went over to the funerals for three of the girls.

01:45:43.000 --> 01:45:54.000
There was still glass in the gutters which I picked we were picking up and shotgun shells were the police had fired over the heads of the people coming out of the bomb church.

01:45:54.000 --> 01:45:59.000
And to me that was the absolute worst day in the movement.

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:06.000
Sharp shooters on the roofs of buildings with the guns pointed down at the crowds in the street.

01:46:06.000 --> 01:46:11.000
Which sort of makes you wonder.

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:20.000
Did you then coming back with a more difficult to get involved in movement activity over you more determined?

01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:21.000
Oh, we were right back.

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:24.000
What I was a stiff student at Tugaloo we were right back into it.

01:46:24.000 --> 01:46:26.000
We were by then having the church visits.

01:46:26.000 --> 01:46:27.000
Talk about that.

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:30.000
The church visits had started that summer.

01:46:30.000 --> 01:46:41.000
I think maybe just before Medgar was killed but while the cattle barns were being filled up with demonstrators in Jackson.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:50.000
And to try to speak to the conscience of the people going to church, you know, we welcome Jesus.

01:46:50.000 --> 01:46:57.000
And integrated groups we go to the churches and sometimes the police would move in and arrest them.

01:46:57.000 --> 01:47:01.000
Sometimes they would be turned away and leave.

01:47:01.000 --> 01:47:04.000
The police arrested them. It was before they had a chance to leave.

01:47:04.000 --> 01:47:07.000
And of course there would be spotters.

01:47:07.000 --> 01:47:13.000
And my fall when I got back it was.

01:47:13.000 --> 01:47:19.000
Ministers would sometimes come down from the north and try to visit their denomination with some.

01:47:19.000 --> 01:47:24.000
It would be a black and white group of ministers.

01:47:24.000 --> 01:47:26.000
What have you?

01:47:26.000 --> 01:47:28.000
And every once in a while you get in church.

01:47:28.000 --> 01:47:32.000
Can you remember those occasion?

01:47:32.000 --> 01:47:35.000
I think fonderened Presbyterian I got into.

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:38.000
I remember.

01:47:38.000 --> 01:47:40.000
I don't remember.

01:47:40.000 --> 01:47:41.000
I honestly don't remember.

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:47.000
But we always knew that the Catholic church and the chance we were a sanctuary if we were downtown.

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:50.000
We would know that for years.

01:47:50.000 --> 01:47:55.000
If you're trapped downtown, if you can make it to the Catholics, your homes safe.

01:47:55.000 --> 01:48:02.000
Was that based on the medieval concept of sanctuary in Catholic church or was it so local?

01:48:02.000 --> 01:48:04.000
I think this was the local priest.

01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:13.000
But the Catholics had been more open to everyone.

01:48:13.000 --> 01:48:18.000
Come unto me, all ye labor and are heavily late and I will give you rest.

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:22.000
Galloway Memorial Methodist Church was a major target.

01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:24.000
Yes.

01:48:24.000 --> 01:48:30.000
So the deacons out on the steps during your way?

01:48:30.000 --> 01:48:35.000
The downtown churches were big and Joyce Ladner Ladner Ladner, who was my roommate,

01:48:35.000 --> 01:48:41.000
ended up married to this gentleman who was an ambassador somewhere in Africa.

01:48:41.000 --> 01:48:49.000
And a group of Methodist ministers were coming to visit and she was being the lovely ambassadors wife serving tea.

01:48:49.000 --> 01:48:51.000
And, oh, where are you from?

01:48:51.000 --> 01:48:52.000
Oh, and what church?

01:48:52.000 --> 01:48:53.000
Oh, Galway.

01:48:53.000 --> 01:48:57.000
Oh, I was arrested on the steps of your church.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:48:58.000
Go Joyce Ladner Ladner.

01:48:58.000 --> 01:49:02.000
There must have been an interesting conversation.

01:49:02.000 --> 01:49:07.000
But I mean, things go around a lot.

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:08.000
Well, I've had it.

01:49:08.000 --> 01:49:20.000
I mean, the Reverend W.B. Selah Minister resigned when his church was not allowed an integrated service.

01:49:20.000 --> 01:49:21.000
Yeah.

01:49:21.000 --> 01:49:23.000
And there's been a radical change.

01:49:23.000 --> 01:49:30.000
But I've met people in recent years in Mississippi who, by way of introduction and explaining who they were,

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:39.000
my father was one of the signers of the statement of conscience that the 28 or 30 whatever ministers came up with.

01:49:39.000 --> 01:49:43.000
And Methodist and most were forced from their churches in Mississippi.

01:49:43.000 --> 01:49:48.000
But still, that's a way of identifying themselves.

01:49:48.000 --> 01:49:55.000
It's extremely difficult to be widened Mississippi and to do anything except be quiet or support the citizens council.

01:49:55.000 --> 01:50:01.000
Or risk as head king and being ostracized throughout the...

01:50:01.000 --> 01:50:02.000
Yeah.

01:50:02.000 --> 01:50:07.000
And it's understandable those that didn't make a loud noise.

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:14.000
But an awful lot of people did things quietly and, you know, somewhat behind the scene.

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:22.000
And so I can understand the current Pope may well have opposed the dictators in Argentina.

01:50:22.000 --> 01:50:27.000
I can believe every word that he was working behind the scenes.

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:34.000
Spraying a 64 graduation day has something people look forward to.

01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:38.000
And Moody writes about it in her book, What Were Your Thoughts?

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:42.000
And had you decided then what you were going to do after graduation?

01:50:42.000 --> 01:50:47.000
Contrary to what Anne says, I was not planning to come back for Freedom Summer.

01:50:47.000 --> 01:50:53.000
I had already decided that I had come to Mississippi to be a student.

01:50:53.000 --> 01:50:58.000
And it just felt natural to leave when I was no longer.

01:50:58.000 --> 01:51:00.000
Once I got my degree.

01:51:00.000 --> 01:51:06.000
And so the obvious place to go back to was Washington, D.C.

01:51:06.000 --> 01:51:09.000
The summer project later known as Freedom Summer.

01:51:09.000 --> 01:51:10.000
Plans were underway.

01:51:10.000 --> 01:51:14.000
Were you actively involved in any of those activities?

01:51:14.000 --> 01:51:15.000
I could type, man.

01:51:15.000 --> 01:51:16.000
I could type.

01:51:16.000 --> 01:51:23.000
And I remember with Bob Moses at the Freedom House on Rose Street, we were talking about it.

01:51:23.000 --> 01:51:34.000
And he was just agonizing over, do we have the right to encourage students to come down for the summer knowing that someone will be killed?

01:51:34.000 --> 01:51:35.000
That's interesting.

01:51:35.000 --> 01:51:38.000
Because that was a question throughout.

01:51:38.000 --> 01:51:44.000
You know, we can tell them that someone is going to be, but they really won't understand.

01:51:44.000 --> 01:51:51.000
Now, actually, that was almost killed the stop freedom summer on the road back from Canton.

01:51:51.000 --> 01:51:54.000
Talk about that.

01:51:54.000 --> 01:51:59.000
Canton had been completely off limits to whites in the movement.

01:51:59.000 --> 01:52:02.000
It was such a rough cow.

01:52:02.000 --> 01:52:05.000
And it was under curfew.

01:52:05.000 --> 01:52:07.000
School year was over.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:09.000
Freedom summer was looming.

01:52:09.000 --> 01:52:19.000
Over at Ed Kings, we decided to take a carload of everyone white in the car to the mass meeting that night.

01:52:19.000 --> 01:52:29.000
It was Ed's car, but decided to be better to let Hamid Kizilbash drive.

01:52:29.000 --> 01:52:32.000
Sworthy white.

01:52:32.000 --> 01:52:37.000
And the meeting was over before the curfews of people could get home.

01:52:37.000 --> 01:52:42.000
Notice we weren't being followed when we left campus and heading into Canton.

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:44.000
And we weren't being followed by the police.

01:52:44.000 --> 01:52:50.000
There were no police around when we left, but realize that we were being followed.

01:52:50.000 --> 01:52:52.000
And the interstate had just opened.

01:52:52.000 --> 01:52:58.000
And we were in that sort of little nomans land between the old road and the new road and the interstate.

01:52:58.000 --> 01:53:05.000
We've been followed and we got boxed off out in that little stretch.

01:53:05.000 --> 01:53:07.000
And guys with crowbars coming out.

01:53:07.000 --> 01:53:24.000
Now a couple days before, the day before, the leader of the opposition party in the legislature of parliament in India had been arrested in Jackson going Gandhi in style in sympathy with us to arrest Rod.

01:53:24.000 --> 01:53:39.000
And this had upset the embassy in Washington, who had passed the word to the State Department, which passed it down to the state of Mississippi, who obviously passed it on to local law enforcement officials.

01:53:39.000 --> 01:53:51.000
I was in the back seat. Ed was in the front with Hamid and long story, but he got the door open beating on Hamid and Ed telling him, don't hit him.

01:53:51.000 --> 01:53:58.000
He's a foreigner. He's not part of, you know, we're whites, we're local.

01:53:58.000 --> 01:54:05.000
He's a foreigner. He's from India. He's from India. Don't hit him. He's from India.

01:54:05.000 --> 01:54:17.000
And Hamid is dazed and bleeding. I'm from Pakistan. I'm from India. What's that? That's his city in India.

01:54:17.000 --> 01:54:27.000
And the guy that Ed was making eye contact with the most who seemed to be the leader, gradually pulled the others off.

01:54:27.000 --> 01:54:34.000
Suggesting that he had gotten the word and had law enforcement connections.

01:54:34.000 --> 01:54:39.000
And we got out of there.

01:54:39.000 --> 01:54:45.000
The governor had said that there would be no violence. There was no violence. And if there was, he wanted to be the first to know.

01:54:45.000 --> 01:54:52.000
So we went to the governor's mansion, but dripping blood up the steps, Ed and Hamid.

01:54:52.000 --> 01:54:58.000
And once they realized, they were there, the governor was, you know, couldn't get in, went to the hospital.

01:54:58.000 --> 01:55:07.000
And we stopped at the state highway, we were told on the way. And they said, if you have a problem, we have to go back to Canton and tell them, well, you know, that was not a pretty picture.

01:55:07.000 --> 01:55:13.000
Then the governor's mansion, then the hospital.

01:55:13.000 --> 01:55:24.000
And my understanding is that we were supposed to have been killed that night to stop freedom of summer.

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:32.000
This comes, Ed said a clan informer or undercover got this word to them.

01:55:33.000 --> 01:55:41.000
The fact that we didn't die that night meant that three other guys did. Two of them were our friends.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:49.000
Goodman, Schwerner, Chaney were on campus a lot. We knew them.

01:55:49.000 --> 01:55:55.000
So that was sort of your last, not your last memory of Mississippi, but the last confrontation?

01:55:55.000 --> 01:55:59.000
My last confrontation was almost being offered up for freedom summer.

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:05.000
And then you were back home and you were reading about the deaths of the civil rights work and everything.

01:56:05.000 --> 01:56:10.000
What were your feelings, Ed? Did you second-guess yourself? Did you wish you were back in it?

01:56:10.000 --> 01:56:15.000
No, but, you know, you knew they were dead.

01:56:15.000 --> 01:56:18.000
I was working at the Smithsonian.

01:56:18.000 --> 01:56:28.000
And I guess I got on with a few of the black workers well enough that they knew I was one of them.

01:56:29.000 --> 01:56:34.000
I was always a question with who was I one of?

01:56:34.000 --> 01:56:41.000
This had been on campus with the visiting white ministers who thought I was one of them, as opposed to the students who thought I was one of them.

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:43.000
There were just some weird moments.

01:56:43.000 --> 01:56:53.000
But one of the black workers told me that they had brought in Chaney's body on the weekend after dark.

01:56:54.000 --> 01:56:59.000
To be examined by the forensic people there, and there was not a bone in his body.

01:56:59.000 --> 01:57:01.000
It was not broken.

01:57:01.000 --> 01:57:08.000
Now this never saw anything in the press. This was just weird in the hallways, which I tend to believe.

01:57:08.000 --> 01:57:15.000
Well, it did get into the press because a doctor spain from the Medical Committee for Human Rights examined it.

01:57:16.000 --> 01:57:24.000
And it was that famous comment that went all over the world saying, you know, any time I've seen a body so beaten up was in an airplane crash.

01:57:24.000 --> 01:57:32.000
So that word did get out, but more in the original with the Mississippi examiner's nothingness.

01:57:32.000 --> 01:57:43.000
Now I've seen references to it, you know, badly beaten every bow, you know, all this, but I didn't hear it in the Smithsonian.

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:46.000
Well, I mean, that was the original story that went out.

01:57:46.000 --> 01:57:59.000
And that was why Dr. David Spain's examination, which he made the request of Fannie Lee Chaney, which also took a lot of guts on her part, that then it was just a cover up.

01:58:00.000 --> 01:58:15.000
And we don't know exactly what went on, but the best evidence we have from informers is that both Goodman and Schwerner were shocked.

01:58:15.000 --> 01:58:23.000
And the Cheney tried to run away, and they literally beat him before the shock.

01:58:24.000 --> 01:58:38.000
But it was it was the kind of thing that part of freedom summer was to get the attention of the world, you know, the sad way that did and things started to change after that.

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:48.000
This whole thing of being brought in the body bag after dark on the weekend and through it was just being whispered around the halls of the Smithsonian at that point.

01:58:49.000 --> 01:59:00.000
So you said you came back for the Meredith March, was that your first time in Mississippi F back from after you left or had you gone down before?

01:59:00.000 --> 01:59:04.000
Well, the Meredith March was 1966.

01:59:04.000 --> 01:59:11.000
I don't think I'd been back, though I might have. I've been in and out of Mississippi regularly over the years.

01:59:11.000 --> 01:59:14.000
The Meredith March went back for that.

01:59:14.000 --> 01:59:17.000
Where did you pick up the Meredith March?

01:59:17.000 --> 01:59:19.000
At Tugaloo.

01:59:19.000 --> 01:59:28.000
I mean, that was the idea when some of us went from Washington Street to Tugaloo, to couples.

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:38.000
And somebody had to have given me some papers that I folded and slipped into my new testament that I always carried on demonstrations.

01:59:38.000 --> 01:59:43.000
You're having a sit-in or a tense moment reading the Bible was a thing to do.

01:59:43.000 --> 01:59:55.000
And they must have been the very first references to Black Power and on a flyer.

01:59:55.000 --> 02:00:07.000
One was from reading it with issued the night that they were in Canton.

02:00:07.000 --> 02:00:10.000
And the other was the next morning.

02:00:10.000 --> 02:00:13.000
The two one was just a half of a legal sheet.

02:00:13.000 --> 02:00:21.000
And the morning one was an explanation of why we're calling for a boycott.

02:00:21.000 --> 02:00:24.000
I keep wondering if that really is the first printed reference.

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:31.000
But the cry Black Power came up the week before in Greenwood.

02:00:31.000 --> 02:00:33.000
And this was the week later in Canton.

02:00:33.000 --> 02:00:44.000
And a week later the Washington Post political cartoon has Black Power, something like SNCC and Grey Power or something,

02:00:44.000 --> 02:00:50.000
and double ACP and the political cartoon and the post, which at that point was a very prominent...

02:00:50.000 --> 02:00:51.000
I'm terrible.

02:00:51.000 --> 02:00:54.000
Yeah, I don't think this was her blocks.

02:00:54.000 --> 02:01:01.000
If you had something in the post that was second-large in the New York Times, newspapers meant something.

02:01:01.000 --> 02:01:07.000
Yeah, that was the March where Black Power was born.

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:14.000
The movement began to go in a different direction than although Blacks had been talking about power for a long time before.

02:01:14.000 --> 02:01:23.000
But now, stokely, for all that Black Power, we went back to his pontificating days and the demonstrations with Nag and the Freedom Ride.

02:01:23.000 --> 02:01:31.000
And in the mid-70s he was speaking at the Smithsonian, probably one of Bernice Regan's King Day programs.

02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:37.000
And I had taken down my youngest two who, at most, were four.

02:01:37.000 --> 02:01:40.000
And stokely was the speaker.

02:01:40.000 --> 02:01:44.000
And probably the most feared man in white America.

02:01:44.000 --> 02:01:51.000
And there was a break and people could, you know, mill about restrooms, whatever.

02:01:52.000 --> 02:01:56.000
And I said to my friends, I was sitting with Black and particularly white, I remember it.

02:01:56.000 --> 02:01:58.000
I'm going to take the kids out.

02:01:58.000 --> 02:02:02.000
I must have just had the two to meet stokely.

02:02:02.000 --> 02:02:05.000
As, oh, Joan, don't. Something will happen.

02:02:05.000 --> 02:02:08.000
And they'll be upsetting and they won't understand.

02:02:08.000 --> 02:02:10.000
No, I'm going to do it.

02:02:10.000 --> 02:02:20.000
So I take the twins out these little freckled face, blonde, Irish looking kids, St. Patrick's Day.

02:02:20.000 --> 02:02:21.000
And I just meet stokely.

02:02:21.000 --> 02:02:32.000
Now between stokely and the lobby and the entrance from Constitution Avenue is a semicircle of bodyguards from the nation.

02:02:32.000 --> 02:02:37.000
Looking very intimidating.

02:02:37.000 --> 02:02:40.000
Stokely is talking to some officials.

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:42.000
I catch his eye.

02:02:42.000 --> 02:02:44.000
He cuts off the conversation with the big wigs.

02:02:44.000 --> 02:02:46.000
Motions me over.

02:02:46.000 --> 02:02:48.000
Stokely, I'd like you.

02:02:48.000 --> 02:02:51.000
Like my kids to meet you.

02:02:51.000 --> 02:02:54.000
And I stokely was what, 6263?

02:02:54.000 --> 02:03:08.000
This towering, fearful figure, knelt on the floor to talk eyeball to eyeball to them, shake their hands and watch your name and how old are you and all this little stuff.

02:03:08.000 --> 02:03:10.000
I mean, we were all friends.

02:03:10.000 --> 02:03:11.000
Yeah.

02:03:11.000 --> 02:03:15.000
And that counted more than the raised fist.

02:03:15.000 --> 02:03:29.000
And I've heard other white folks who knew him from back in the day with similar stories of him going out of his way to acknowledge their presence and interact with them.

02:03:30.000 --> 02:03:39.000
And one point from Duke who said that she was at the speech to still play Gage.

02:03:39.000 --> 02:03:43.000
One of the fired brimstone speech and afterward the word.

02:03:43.000 --> 02:03:48.000
They went back to this guy's house and drank wine and listen to classical music.

02:03:48.000 --> 02:03:50.000
You know Joan Browning.

02:03:50.000 --> 02:03:51.000
Yes.

02:03:51.000 --> 02:03:57.000
She has a story of stokely going out of his way to come over and interact in that.

02:03:57.000 --> 02:04:02.000
It's too bad that that image is the only one that most people will have.

02:04:02.000 --> 02:04:08.000
Tell us, this is, we thank you so much, but we want to know something about your life in the last 50 years.

02:04:08.000 --> 02:04:11.000
Could you tell us what you've been doing?

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:18.000
Well, I came back and worked a number of menial jobs because don't hire women.

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:21.000
They just get married, have babies and quit.

02:04:21.000 --> 02:04:24.000
So I got married and had babies and quit.

02:04:24.000 --> 02:04:37.000
Five other boys involved in the community, things and the schools and PTAs and speaking for the school board.

02:04:37.000 --> 02:04:45.000
A number of times on issues that you could trace back to the civil rights movement perspective.

02:04:45.000 --> 02:04:53.000
In the classroom as a teaching assistant for close to 30 years and brought a lot of perspectives.

02:04:53.000 --> 02:05:02.000
And just thinking outside the box and appreciation of understanding of cultural issues to the classroom.

02:05:02.000 --> 02:05:10.000
Now that I'm retired from that, I'm still speaking.

02:05:10.000 --> 02:05:22.000
Still anybody who's writing a book or making a movie or wants to do an oral history and wants a speaker for an event or a care of a family.

02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:27.000
So if there are community college classroom, I'm happy to go.

02:05:27.000 --> 02:05:31.000
Well, with that in mind, I would like to particularly if they feed me.

02:05:31.000 --> 02:05:32.000
Thank you.

02:05:32.000 --> 02:05:35.000
And this has been an enlightening interview.

02:05:35.000 --> 02:05:48.000
But before we go, I want to add that one of Joan Trump, our Mohawk son, Loki Mulholland, has a video documentary about his mother's life titled An Ordinary Hero,

02:05:48.000 --> 02:05:50.000
the true story of Joan Mohawk.

02:05:50.000 --> 02:05:53.000
We'll get a zero in on that right away.

02:05:53.000 --> 02:05:57.000
And what a fitting tribute and from your son.

02:05:57.000 --> 02:05:58.000
Amazing.

02:05:58.000 --> 02:05:59.000
Make you very proud.

02:05:59.000 --> 02:06:02.000
I had to do something right raising him.

02:06:02.000 --> 02:06:03.000
Thanks again.

02:06:03.000 --> 02:06:04.000
Thank you.

02:06:04.000 --> 02:06:05.000
Oh, that was great.

02:06:05.000 --> 02:06:07.000
That was terrific.

02:06:07.000 --> 02:06:17.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

